RRIssueLogBody194:
"Recently I penned a letter of recommendation for Tatiana Reeves in her pursuit of various teaching positions, including a position with NYC Teaching Fellows. As her supervisor I was happy to offer my support for her candidacy and proud when I was told she had been accepted.  It is with regret that I must withdraw my recommendation in the strongest terms and inform you of the recent circumstances that gave rise to this difficult decision.

Tatiana has been a member of my staff at Citizen Schools for the 2015-2016 school year.  She was recently admitted to the Hawai'i corps and, as a native Hawaiian, plans to return to teach there this year.  As a educator, I believe it would be an egregious mistake to allow her to continue to work as a teacher. This opinion is shared by my deputy director and managing director or program, who have cosigned this letter.

Although Tatiana does exhibit some positive qualities, including strong organizational and logistical planning, her lack of professionalism and insubordination has reached such an extreme that I feel compelled to write and inform you of her behavior. 

On Wednesday, May 18th, Tati came in 50 minutes late. It was clear that she was frustrated, and as has become typical, she proceeded to express her frustration in a deeply appropriate fashion.  She proceeded to take items in the office and throw and slam them on the floor.  When asked to stop, she rudely and dismissively insisted she was just moving things, she was then asked to be calm and interact professionally, she responded, you cant talk to me like that.  She was asked to leave for the day to collect herself, to which she responded, if I leave I am not coming back.  

While quitting less than 30 minutes before she was due to teach a class in such a grossly insubordinate fashion would have been disruptive enough to call into question her ability to conduct herself as a professional, she proceeded to attend her class and inform her students that she was leaving, effective immediately, due to a conflict with her assistant director.  This was extremely traumatic for the students, and required a great deal of administrative triage, including a session with the social worker. And yet, Ms. Reeves did not stop there. She proceeded to find the Principal and Assistant Principal and plead her case to them, laying out all the deficits she detected in our program. 

While this incident was isolated in its intensity, it was neither surprising nor an uncommon display.  Tati has demonstrated difficulty self-regulating her emotions on multiple occasions.  She often yells at fellow Americorps members and her supervisors (myself and my assistant director).  She frequently arrives late to work, she has missed 50% of her team meetings with our regional staff, and her attitude has been poison to our culture. 

The culture and experience of Teaching Fellows requires humility, resilience, a growth mindset, and stewardship.  As an alumna of the program, I feel confident that Tatiana is not a good fit.  She has shown extreme disrespect, and has damaged the relationship of our organization with our school partners.  She has shown that the workload of teaching 3 hours a day, 4 days a week is too overwhelming for her to handle emotionally or professionally.  It is my professional opinion that the more rigorous demands of NYC Teaching Fellows will preclude her from thriving as a corps member.

Therefore, it is with regret and apologies that I withdraw my recommendation. 

Sincerely, 

Amanda Goodman, Ed.M
Campus Director, Citizen Schools

Joseph Colarusso, Esq. 
Deputy Campus Director, Citizen Schools

Aimee Baez, Ed.M
Managing Director of Program, Citizen Schools NYNJ"

I originally applied when I was about to graduate college in 2004. RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I have reapplied to Teaching Fellows again because I feel I am more qualified to be a fellow. I have first hand experience writing unit plans, lesson plans, and classroom management and maintaining portfolios for varying subjects. I have taught English and Social Studies in a high risk are and low-income area. This experience has made me a stronger candidate because I understand the difficulties of being in the classroom and creating things such as bulletin boards. I have taught from 6th-8th grade and even have different after-school programs, which I lead, in my school.

After being passed on by New York City Teaching Fellows, I have continued to service youth in underprivileged low-income neighborhoods; gaining more relative experience as I continue my pursuit to enrich the minds of the next generation. In the few years since my last application, I have developed student leadership programs for upperclassmen, organized coed sports building leagues, facilitated community engagement activities to bridge a connection between youth and their surrounding neighborhoods; adding further exposure to the dynamic personalities and circumstances of today's youth. I also gained further exposure to special needs populations and became an active participant in workshops that cater to special education populations. Being an educator from a creative arts background has come with many limitations; New York City Teaching Fellows provides the ultimate pathway to become a certified educator and continue my pursuit and passion to enrich the minds of the youth, our future leaders of tomorrow.

Having decided to pursue a Ed.M. at Harvard Graduate School of Education in order to developed critical, nuanced, and innovative perspectives on the field of education, I feel highly motivated to return to the classroom and apply the promising theories toward building actionable knowledge and better futures for students. As I continue my work in jails, foster systems, and under resourced schools, it is no longer enough for me to accept the limitations of my roles as mentor, advocate, and educator, feeling overwhelmed by my inability to address the roots of why so many youth are disengaged and violated. I want to translate my personal observations and theoretical knowledge into sustained relationships, iterative design, and reflective action that reverses the flow of power and knowledge production toward those who are misrepresented and underrepresented. This means supporting individual and communal capacities for critical inquiry and social action; this means building relationships of trust and mutuality; this means, in Lisa Delpits words, learning to be vulnerable enough to allow our world to turn upside down in order to allow the realities of others to edge themselves into our consciousness.  I will not be satisfied with analyzing the experiences of others. My subjective interpretations are insufficient, especially when they feign neutrality. I will collaborate with communities to sharpen our analytical tools, creating new literacies that will be carried forth into new realities. What does this look like in action? What assumptions can I subvert and what alternate realities can I create? Having authored case studies, annotated bibliographies, and achieved the highest academic award in my undergraduate studies, I am still unsatisfied with the answers I have encountered and struggle to translate theory into action. I need a multiplicity of perspectives and experiences to proceed with my studies and work with greater intentionality. Individual and collective freedom is the hard-earned struggle of returning to oneself and each other through the deconstruction of internal and external barriers.  My graduate work thus far has been in preparation for my return to New York where I hope to design powerful learning experiences for students and learn from as well as support other teachers.

RRIssueLogBody194:
Spoke to Shakira to issue EPT CL. She was a bit defensive and used a tone throughout the call, however, she did understand her next steps.  
She shared that she thought she would have the opportunity to teach in 3 content areas but has only been teaching in Math. Since the focus of technique assessment was ELA, which she hasnt been teaching, she thought she could use one that was already written. She didn't realize she was getting graded on her ability to write the lesson plan. She also said that the stretch it questions were her own (how, what, why?) She shared that she was told that she could use a lesson that they already had, but since she had only been teaching math and didn't have an ELA lesson (which was what they were required to use in the Technique Assessment) that she is at a disadvantage. I reiterated that the techniques are based on a teacher's ability to ask good questions and plan lessons and therefore, she could not use an exemplar plan. 
She also mentioned that she thinks expectations are unclear for using phones since she was told fellows cant have phone out but then there is an expectation that you are checking your email/phone with scheduling and are able to respond to emails and quick changes. I reiterated that her coach mentioned she was on facebook, which she should not be on at any point.

She unknowingly teaches me about some of the obstacles she faces coming from a single-parent home and a low-income community. Finally, after university I continued to play field hockey for an international, adult league where I have experienced many different individuals and cultures. As the league is diverse, I have had the opportunity to meet and learn from individuals from the Caribbean, to Europe, to the Middle East. All of these experiences support my aspiration to become a teacher. I advocate for education and I believe, as a teacher, I will be able to support the need for positive role models in the public school system. I desire challenge and I have learned to not fear hardships, but to find creative ways to overcome obstacles. I appreciate diversity and understand all individuals have a different story to tell. I was fortunate enough to gain so many academic, athletic, and corporate experiences throughout my life and I believe, even more so now, I would be successful as an NYC Teaching Fellow.

I am a stronger candidate this time around because I have been exposed to working with children in a group setting. I am currently an aide at a daycare and because of this experience I want more than ever to be a teacher.

Last time I applied for a spot in New York City Teaching Fellows was in 2014 during my senior year of undergraduate study. Since then, I completed my first Masters Degree in African Studies from Stanford, added two additional years of work experience to my repertoire, and spent one summer teaching Syrian refugees English in Turkey. My graduate education confirmed my love for learning as a constant form of intellectual engagement, and most importantly as a path towards growth. 

My two additional years of work experience were in a few different settings, including the Abbasi Program of Islamic Studies at Stanford, Gotham City Restaurant near my home, and Change.org office in the Chelsea section of New York City. I reflected every day on how I could've done better, and made it a point to never stop learning in all settings. 

Lastly, my time teaching in Turkey changed my life. My students were Syrian refugees, and they taught me more about the world and life than I taught them. Classrooms are not just about the material, but how it is transmitted, and how and why students believe the material is of value or not. Education is not effectively delivered without a strong understanding of the context of students' lives. Luckily, I befriended my students as a mentor, and gained their trust. That trust allowed them to channel their motivation toward learning English each and every single day. 

Altogether, these experiences have changed who I am as a person and a professional, and I'm reapplying because I want to dedicate my life to education.

I applied to the NYC Teaching Fellowship last fall, and was extremely motivated to pursue my goal of becoming a teacher.  After three years in the business world I understood the type of life that I wanted to pursue, and the type of impact that I wanted to make.  I made the decision to follow my parents' path (both have been teachers for over 25 years), and pursue a career in education.  After completing the application process, I waited for three months to hear back from the program.  Unfortunately, I eventually received the news that I had not been accepted to the fellowship.  As a result, I was forced to pursue other opportunities that were available to me at that time.  However, a month after I received the initial email, I received another email stating that there had been a system error, and I had indeed been accepted into the program.  But in the month between these emails, I had committed to another job.  This was a heartbreaking experience for me.

It was an experience that forced me to rethink the type of career I wanted to pursue. I now realize that I do in fact belong in the classroom.  I am now more motivated than ever to become a teacher. RRIssueLogBody194:
Moved back to SJU after emailing Trevor and Dan Weisberg

Hi Mr. Soponis,

     I hope all is well. My name is Jamecia Forsythe, and I am currently a NYC Teaching Fellow. Recently we were given our university assignments, and I was given St. John's University. Since I have to take care of my father who has prostate cancer (I can provide any necessary medical records/documents regarding his condition if needed), and since I live in Brooklyn, I put in an appeal to my university, requesting that I be put in Brooklyn so that it would be easier for me to take care of my father, while participating in this program. When I got the appeal decision, I was given Relay GSE, but when I saw the class schedule for Relay GSE, I knew instantly that I would have a problem committing to that schedule because there is less flexibility; therefore I contacted a representative from NYCTF and they told me that the only schools that participates my in subject area are Lehman, Relay GSE, and SJU. However, I never knew that those were my only three options because if I did, I would have never put in that appeal because regardless of whatever school I was given, because of the important fact that I could not stay in Brooklyn, and that I would have to venture out regardless. I was never told that Relay GSE, SJU, and Lehman were the only options I had before I put in my appeal, which makes me feel mislead because I never knew my options were limited (because I thought our chances were with all of the schools in the program), and especially because I had no chance of remaining in Brooklyn. Even though the summer coursework has to be in Queens for SJU, I have the opportunity to take the rest of my classes on the Manhattan campus, with the same flexibility; so I would have fought my way through this summer because looking into the long run, this summer is simply a small feat considering the rest of the program; I would have dealt with the commute for the few months because I know that I can take the rest of my courses in Manhattan. SJU would be a better fit because I can schedule classes for one day, and continue to aid with my father. I understand that the university assignments are final, but I feel mislead because I was never able to explore all of my options, and it lead me to make an uneducated decision, that I would have never made if I knew that my options were limited to three schools, as opposed to schools in Brooklyn, let alone, the rest of the schools. I love everything that this program has to offer, and I worked hard to be in it, and I am excited to teach the new generation. I would hate to have to leave the program and have to do the whole process over because of a simple conflict with a school schedule. I am not asking for any leniency for anything within the realm of NYCTF's pre-service training, just a fair chance to have the best fit with the information I was told only after the appeal. Overall, I just would like to know if you can help me so that I can please go back to my original assignment because it SJU allows me more flexibility, and I would be able to still take care of my father and get my work done, and so that I can continue being a fellow of this cohort (27) and eventually become an effective teacher. I know this was a long email, thank you in advance for your consideration, and I look forward to hearing from you. If you would like, you can contact me through this email address (JameciaForsythe@Gmail.com), or by phone 347.255.8446. 

Thank you
Jamecia F.

After failing to make it into the Fellows program this past April, I decided to really reflect on my desire to be involved with the program.  I want to be an educator, and I want to make a difference in the lives of children the way my teachers made a difference in mine.  I began to volunteer my time and ideas to my son's day care facility so that I could spend more time with children, some of whom have special needs. In working with children on a regular basis, I realized that education strongly remains my calling.  The Teaching Fellows program is an innovative, and unique way for someone like me, who is a career changer, to enter a field in which I can really change lives.  The development of children has always been fascinating to me, and this program truly teaches what it means to be an educator.  
I am a stronger candidate this time around because I have devoted so much more time and energy into learning and understanding children, and I truly comprehend what a commitment it is to be a leader in an educational setting.  I have taught young children, with guidance from the lead teacher, how to express themselves using art and music.  I have introduced a "feelings" wall that has allowed children to express how they are feeling when it seems that no one is listening.  I have become very attached to these children, and continuously come up with ways to teach them more than I did during our last session.  My commitment to education is even stronger this time around, and I still firmly believe that the Teaching Fellows program is the best path for my goals.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I have always been motivated to reapply. Teaching is my dream and I will continue to strive for this goal. I believe I am a stronger candidate this year because I have experience more of life. I have gained more knowledge of the world. It has made me more aware of the downfalls of the education system and I have many ideas that I want to implement to try to combat them.

As an AmeriCorps VISTA, I work to help families who are in poverty. VISTA programs are all centrally focused on eliminating poverty in America, an  I believe education is so important to create a more equal future. Though I am thankful for the compulsory education we enjoy in America, there are still many disparities in the quality of education children receive. These disparities are often based on skin color and economic status. . Regardless of these factors, every child should be able to achieve in school, and discover subjects they are passionate about: This is the philosophy that New York Teaching Fellows strives to make a reality, and I'd like to be a part of this effort. I am a stronger candidate this year, because I've gained valuable experience working in low-income communities as a VISTA for Indianapolis Public Schools. I've learned about the many boundaries low-income students face when trying to achieve in school, and have participated in the many practices IPS uses to boost student achievement. In a district where 100 percent of the student population receives subsidized lunch, IPS struggles to raise student achievement. The district is using many methods to combat factors that inhibit student achievement. For instance, Parent Involvement Educators help parents support their children's schooling, and College and Career Readiness Counselors to prepare students for college. Curriculum is focused on skills students can use in their adult lives, while teachers and administrators receive more training on how to engage students in material through alternate teaching methods. I can use many of the teaching methods I've learned working in IPS in my own classroom.

In January of 2015, I failed the in-person interview component of the NYC Teaching Fellows because I missed the lesson plan component of the process. I learned to humble myself after a mortifying experience of teaching a completely irrelevant lesson among my group. I am a stronger candidate since I last applied because now I am painfully aware that I need to download and plan according to the lesson plan template that is emailed to candidates before I get ahead of myself.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I first applied to NYCTF last year, and learned a lot throughout the whole process.  Although I was able to get all the way to the in-person teaching sample, ultimately, I wasn't accepted into the program at that time.  I was, of course, disappointed.  However, I feel that having gone through the process last year has definitely helped me to understand fully what is expected of a teaching fellow when in the program and left me more determined to succeed this year.
My friend and roommate is currently in the second year of the program and watching her delegate tasks, manage her time, and prepare for the students she teaches every day has opened my eyes to the amount of work she has undertaken and I am excited to get to work myself!

The factors that motivated me to reapply to the program are more experiences and skills. I also know that my former director from Queens Community House was accepted in the program and someone from Harlem RBI was accepted in the program. Lastly a good friend of mine encouraged me to apply again. I feel that since the last time that I applied, I gained more experience with working with children. I worked in a summer camp for Queens Community House as an assistant, then because of my work ethic, punctuality, and the way I worked with the kids I was offered to come back as an assistant again in September of last year. There I worked with elementary school age children from different backgrounds and cultures which influenced how the parents and kids interacted in school or with the teachers, and after school/summer camp programs. I soon left because I was offered a better opportunity to join Harlem RBI as a learning coach apart of AMERICORP. It was a different experience for me because I learned how kids and their families from low income communities affect how they perform in school. Their socioeconmic status plays a big role for the kids, their families and the program. I learned to adjust to each kids needs and learned that I have to stratagiize different ways to deal with the kids disrespectful atttitudes because the way they were in school with me, it is the same way they acted at home, and many of their parents have the same atttitude. My co coach and I had to nagivate and find different ways to communicate to the parents and pull in their interest. I also began working in a day care which was a new experience for me. I decided to broaden my horizens and try working in a day care. It was different for me because I am used to working with kids that know how to speak, use the bathroom themselves, and can do things on their own. Therefore working in the day care was hard but led me to learn to have more patience and understanding. Throughout my experiences working with kids I possessed skills such as identifying child abuse and learned how to identify SIDS and shaken baby syndrome which were new topics to me. My experience working in the restaurant also helped me to learn food saftey practices, I use that when I see food being prepared in the day care. I believe that I am a stronger candidate because I have gained experience, posssess new skills, and learned new traits that will help me when working with children of any age or any socioeconomic  status.

I was accepted last year by the NYC Teaching fellows. However an career opportunity was presented to me that I had to entertain. However during my time at this job I realized more and more that I am still drawn to becoming a teacher. My passion for wanting to teach has grown because of this calling and will help me even further be a strong and successful teacher.

I reapplied for this fellowship, because I firmly believe teaching is what I am meant to do. This program creates great opportunities for people, and it has great goals.  I want to be part of this effort, and I want to make a difference in childrens lives.  Not being accepted into the program last year was disappointing, but I think the application process itself made me a stronger candidate. There were moments of doubt before and after the phone interview.  I second guessed my decision to apply to this program, and then got hung up on how I could have answered differently. On my way home from selection day. I made peace with how I performed, and I knew that if I was not accepted it was because there were stronger applicants than myself, and that was surprisingly empowering. In the last six months, Ive worked on my self-confidence, my ability to learn, to be receptive to criticism, and how to get through situations seemingly out of my control.

I am motivated to reapply to the teaching fellows because I believe in making a difference; I feel like this is my path and it is alined to what I want to do as a career because I was a ESL student and I believe I have the skill set to lead ESL students to the path of success. I believe I am a stronger candidate since I last applied because have gained more experience after meeting with students who didn't posses a positive school environment like I did which encourages me become a teacher for upcoming ESL students in NYC.

The teaching schedule required by the New York City Teaching Fellows Program would have required me to terminate my teaching job at Westchester Community College five weeks into the summer semester of 2015.  In my view, it would have been unethical to leave my students during the semester given that it would have amounted to a failure to live up to my responsibility as a teacher.  Also, I had signed two contracts with Westchester Community College to teach summer courses.  Leaving before the completion of those courses would have been a violation of those contracts.  These obstacles did not diminish my interest in the Teaching Fellows Program.  If I am fortunate enough to be accepted again, my intention is eliminate those obstacles by leaving Westchester Community College at the end of the winter semester and refrain from signing any more contracts to teach any more courses beyond the winter semester.  This would enable me to fulfill the teaching requirement inherent in the Teaching Fellows Program without having to desert my students or break any contracts.

Last year I applied and was invited to a group interview during a very busy time in my life, as I was finishing my masters thesis, working as a teaching assistant and taking graduate classes. I missed the deadline to submit my application twice and finally submitted my application when the deadline was extended. I felt unprepared for the group interview shortly after but I learned a lot from the experience. This year I have gained more teaching experience and would really love a second chance to become a teaching fellow.

I had previously applied to the New York City Teaching Fellows last year. Although I had made it to the group interview stage, I feel like I was flustered when it came to the group interview.  Skipping half of my lesson plan, It was clear that I was very nervous.  Looking back I understand that as an educator one can not get flustered when things go awry. Having confidence, knowing the material, and where you want to go with the material will allow an educator to get back on track.  I understand why I was not selected to proceed further. 
Seeing the positive experience that the Fellowship program is, I hope to leave a more lasting impression this time.

I have always wanted to have a part in peoples betterment. I feel that becoming a part of the education system via the New York City Teaching Fellows would provide me with a perfect opportunity to do so. As a teenager, I felt it was possible to serve this purpose through architecture, but in my experiences since Ive found that the classroom would be my ideal environment to be in. Thank you for your time and consideration.

I decided to reapply for the teaching fellows because my passion for teaching has not changed. I was unable to have my degree conferred in time to begin pre-service training. Throughout this time I was able to meet my degree requirements and study techniques I learned through material offered by the teaching fellows. I have completed all the necessary workshops required by the department of education to become certified. I was excited last year  but i'm even more excited this year because I know my skills as a teacher and future educator has grown tremendously.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: Factors that motivated me to reapply is working with special needs students everyday and seeing how I can make an impact as a teacher. I am really motivated to get my master's degree so I can start my career and make positive changes in my life. I am stronger candidate because I have more experience in a special education classroom and better organization skills. I have to complete progress reports, complete lesson plans and attend preschool meetings. I now have the work ethic and experience to be a NYC Teaching Fellow.

After recovering from a motor vehicle accident, I applied last year to be a new York City teaching fellow. From the moment of disappointment when I wasn't accepted to the program I knew I would reapply and take the year to make sure I was the best candidate possible. Although I knew I was a strong candidate from my resume, transcript, and prior experience I knew there was something missing, my confidence. I know the program is very demanding. I knew I had the work ethic to take on the work load. I worked full-time since I was a sophomore in high school, and completed my bachelor's degree taking night classes while working full time. Last year when I applied even though I felt better and ready to return to the work force after my accident,  I had not been able to go back to work yet. I knew that to have the confidence I had to know that I could not just meet the demands of the program, but could exceed them and excel. So this past year I've done my best to make sure I could do just that. I've worked hard to make sure I was back to 100%, and both physically and mentally ready for the challenge. I started working to regain my confidence in myself and my abilities. I started looking for a job that would help me prepare for becoming a teaching fellow this year. I was looking for a job with similar hours, and called for interaction with students and parents. 

I found what I was looking for, and started working for Healthy Smiles, a school based dental practice, as a Marketer and Dental Assistant. We go to schools all over NYC and provide dental services to children, mainly in low-income neighborhoods without proper access to dental services. As a Marketer, I go to the schools during student drop-off and dismissal, meet with the parents individually, explain our program services, and obtain a signed consent form for their children to participate. I also often give an in-service seminar for parents and teachers where I explain our program, give information on oral hygiene, offer tips to prevent childhood tooth decay, and answer any questions. Once I have collected the consent forms, I go to the school with the dentist and/or hygienist as a dental assistant. Before the Hygienist starts the cleanings for a class, I give the kids a short lesson on oral health and hygiene, then using a custom prop, I demonstrate proper tooth brushing technique. While assisting the dentist I help to calm down children from crying or refusing to participate, with my help they often willingly participate. Working this year with Healthy Smiles, has assured me I am definitely physically and mentally ready to start the NTCTF program. I know I am able to work the hours required while taking a full course-load. More than that, this job has made me want to become a teacher more than ever before. I am now fully confident that I am the candidate you are looking for, and am excited to get started!
My added professional experience and continuous motivation to make a difference as an educator has encouraged my reapplication.

Within the past year, I have been a supervisor and a correction officer, supervising inmates and mental health care coordinators along with case managers. I have been in supervising roles which have not fulfilled me professionally or emotionally. I no longer had direct contact with individuals to support their needs and goals. I have learned being a leader outside the realm of offering direct support is not sustaining for me. Teachers are highly motivating, who instill drive and persistence within the classroom. Ms. Cobb, my fourth grade teacher helped me because she went the extra mile to get to know her students and support them past their academic goals. This was very inspiring.
 
Working with youth, has always been the most rewarding for me. As a teen advisor and program coordinator, I was managing programs but knew it was important to maintain an effort to remain involved and support youth with developing workshops, supporting participants write essays or apply for college.  Introducing government to middle school and high school students was astounding as they learned the process of city and state governments along with the powers they held now and in the future. Educating and empowering young people has always been uplifting for me.  I appreciate the significance of being an educator, who is structured and equipped to deliver the best resources in a classroom. Guiding students in a classroom is powerful and I yearn to be that motivating factor for students in New York City.
I was asked to move on with my candidacy and due to personal health issues that arose around the time I was previously applying the opportunity fell by the wayside.

When I applied to the NYC Teaching Fellows last year I had just been laid off from the job that I had dreamed of in college, was unsure about my future and searching for a new path. I always loved school but had never seriously considered becoming a teacher until I read about the fellows program. Since I was turned down last spring I have spent the past year pursuing other careers, temping and shadowing wherever I could, and casting a wide net in terms of searching for a new career. But every new job I considered only served to remind me that academia is what I'm truly interested in pursuing. In a way I'm grateful to have been rejected the first time I applied as it gave me the opportunity to look into other career paths and reevaluate my goals. I know now that purpose is just as important to me as income, and that to feel truly accomplished I need to pursue a career that challenges me while allowing me to help others.

I am motivated to reapply because my research has convinced me that this is a great program that actually seeks to serve the best interests of students. The duality of being placed in high need schools and having a subsidized masters degree are also motivating factors. Since my last application I have been employed as a paraprofessional and have had the opportunity to work with special education students in an inclusive classroom. These students, along with the special education teacher, have made me realize that many students are in need of specialized learning but are not always at the place where it is available. With this knowledge, I would like to be trained as to how to best help these students achieve academic success.

I really wanted to be a part of the fellows when I initial applied.  I made it all the way to the face to face and thought I was a strong candidate but I was not accepted.  I did not let that discourage me, so that I why I am applying again.  During the face to face, the teachers that were facilitating the class had such passion about the program that I knew it was something I wanted to be part of.  They told such positive stories about their experience and how it changed their lives.  It only made me want it more.

Last year when I applied I had personal experiences with helping my younger cousins with academics and growing up with family members who are autistic and others who have special needs. However, I have grown much more since then, do to being a full time City Year member at P.S 206. I have had the opportunity over the last six months to mentor, tutor and teach 3rd and 4th graders who are from low income communities and who are nest students, which are students of special needs which fall on the autistic spectrum and other special needs. This job has helped me become more patient working with students and it has also helped me learn how to create effective lesson plans for all of my students. Most importantly I am a stronger canidate because now I have experience working with students from low income comunnities with behaviorment managment challenges, special needs student, facilitating lesson plans, creating clubs, and running an afterschool program with my other teammates.

I applied to Teaching Fellows last year, and I had a Selection Day interview scheduled, but I withdrew my application before the interview because I found out that I had been accepted to the City Year New York 2015-2016 Corps, and while I was still interested in NYC Teaching Fellows, City Year felt like a better fit straight out of college with no direct experience in the classroom, in addition to being a safe bet at that point. In retrospect, I believe I made the right decision in delaying my full application to NYC Teaching Fellows, because my interest in going into education in New York City has only grown, and my service with City Year has made me a stronger candidate as well. I am much more confident in my belief that I am ready to teach in a school in a low-income neighborhood in the city, and I got to test the waters without the onus of responsibility of teaching an entire class being on me. While I firmly believed last year that I would make a great teacher when I applied, I know that even just the year's experience has made me stronger.

Additionally, there wasn't anywhere else in the application I felt appropriate to include it, but I wanted to include it here: I'm qualified to be a candidate for Special Education in Social Studies in all ways EXCEPT I don't have three credit hours of college economics on my transcript, which is why I said I am not qualified based on those metrics (regrettably, because history is my main academic passion, and being a high school history teacher- likely special education as well- is my ultimate career aspiration). However, I did take a combined AP Government/Economics class my senior year of high school (one semester of government and one of economics), and I would be able to provide my grades for that upon request if that would qualify me (I got a 5 on the AP Government test- not the issue given I took a number of political science/diplomatic history courses in college- and my school didn't offer any AP Economics test, or else I would have taken it). Alternatively, I would be more than willing to take a course online, at a community college, or through some other appropriate avenue between now and the start of the 2016-2017 school year if that would qualify me. I more than understand if that is not possible, though, and I appreciate the consideration.

I believe that I am a much stronger candidate now since the last time I applied for the New York Teaching Fellows because of my acquired experience working with students of various different backgrounds and learning levels. This wouldn't be a problem if it weren't for the challenges these schools have themselves such as limited resources & staff.  Because these students often fall behind in basic skills such as reading, they are less inclined to want to pursue the classes within the STEM category.  However this isn't the only problem.  The other issue is that teachers for STEM related subjects are often credentialed in something else.  This isn't to say that those will not make excellent teachers.  However I truly believe that to teach something, one has to be invested in that subject material.  This is what motivated me to reapply.  I have taken a deep investment into studying biology. I was put on this earth to teach and every day the feeling becomes greater, Teaching has always been a very strong passion of mine; I have always had a concern in securing the future of the young minds.  Even now I am  up to date with all my nieces and nephews report cards  and  have question all of them  as to what they feel they can improve to get  better grades and have a successful academic year. My concern for the academic achievement of children is what fuels me to become the best teacher I can be.   I want to make a commitment to having a positive effect on student achievement, and also make them feel self-confident enough to pursue any career of their choice.  I am a dedicated individual, and I aim to be a strong positive teacher who in which influences her students. An additional motivation for me to reapply was a very influential teacher; Mr. Ovalles was a history teacher  I had in high school, despite the limited resource he had he always enforce us to do better and strive for the best. He took the responsibility of demanding nothing but the best from his students, he broaden our learning experience by using the internet , old articles, and other methods to intrigue us and to help us remember historical facts. Meeting such an individual like that has always helped push me into the direction of wanting to teach. I feel that I am a stronger candidate since the last time I applied because I know the struggle of growing up with limited resources or learning outlets and still striving and doing my best, by being accepted into this program I will be given the opportunity to help other children find their passion regard less of their economic status or cultural background. On a  macro level this will be a way of me giving  back to the low  income communities  , which I s very important to me  , When I first filled this out my nerves got the best of me and did not allow me to convey the feeling of necessity that I have to give back to low income communities.

The greatest factor which has motivated me during the reapplication process is the recurring urge to enter a career field where I can apply my entire set of life skills to make a difference to people at an age where no person has a concrete impression of the world.  After being in health care for a few years, the thought of teaching remained in the forefront of my experience.  Health care has enabled me to be motivated to teach again because I interact with patients from all different backgrounds.  From new mothers to patients recovering from surgery, everyone has a story to tell and it is part of the healing process to reminisce about the different facets of life, which schooling helps to shape and mold.

I also come from humble beginnings in a small rural town.  This has instilled an empathetic outlook on life wherein each individual becomes the benefactor of their own decisions, and I refuse to enter a career field in which salary and isolated achievement are the primary factors of success.  Of all the lessons any student learns throughout their education, making decisions that involves the well-being of others is a true way to measure progress of the individual while increasing the happiness of those around them.

In order to become stronger, I have increased my volunteering, created a monthly budget to assure my own progress, and helped out at work by doing overtime when the hospital really needs help.

I am still determined to complete my certification and be a teacher in New York City. Since my last application, I have worked more with children, mainly in Early Childhood settings. I am more patient, more focused, and much more understanding of all the aspects that go into learning, and the many different ways there are to learn. I have witnessed other teachers so dedicated to their classrooms, and determined to reach the students and give them this gift of learning. I have seen my mother finally retire from teaching in inner city, low income, Elizabeth, NJ, at age 80, after a 40 year career, having taught multi-generations of families in the neighborhood, have students return over and over, to tell her where they are in life now, books they still remember experiencing with her, things she told them, examples she set. I recognize the responsibility of a teacher is extremely grand, awe-inspiring, and an honor. And, it's also a great way to spend your day, and your life!

I initially applied to the Teaching Fellows program in 2014 for the 2014-2015 school year. I became aware of the program upon the suggestion of a high school principal that I had done some design work for. Since teaching was my first love, and I was getting ready to graduate from college with a degree in Communication Design, I felt like it was fate since I was not satisfied with the idea of using my skills solely for conspicuous consumption. I wanted to use my passion and training for a greater purpose.

I made it to the group interview phase of the process. However, as the appointment drew near, an unfamiliar sense of anxiety began to overwhelm me. I began to question my motives. "Why are you really doing this?" The response was the same, "because you said you always wanted to." I got closer and closer to the interview date, that answer felt inadequate. One the day of the group session, I began to feel like an impostor. The passion for teaching was still in my heart but I had not taken into account how much I had changed as a person over the course of my adulthood. I did not want to be a glorified babysitter that mimicked lesson plans and prepared students for standardized tests that mean absolutely nothing in the real world. I needed to reevaluate my mission.

Over the course of the next few months I began to simplify my life in radical ways, getting rid of all preconceived notions of who I was, stripping myself of the psychological defense mechanisms I had created in order to survive over the past decade. It was an excruciating but liberating process. I reemerged with a stronger sense of purpose. 

I realized that I do not just want to be a teacher, I want to change the way young inner-city students perceive education. I want to help children become masters of their fate, using knowledge as a tool to solve the problems that have plagued their communities for generations. I want my classroom to be a laboratory, where the students are the scientists and the curriculum is the experiment. I hope to use the skills I acquire during my Teaching Fellows experience to develop interactive eLearning environments for learners of all ages, abilities, and backgrounds.

I started off my college career perusing a path in education and I am now striving to pick up where I left off. I never lost my passion to make a difference in low-income schools. I want to play a role in aiding students to achieve high academic standards and provide them with the skills to serve as leaders in the community. I believe I would be a tremendous asset to the NYC Teaching Fellows. My future goal is be apart of the development of our education system. I aspire to one day obtain my Ph. D in Education. I have taken the notes and knowledge from my first experience and I plan on using them to excel even further this go around.

The factors that motivated me to reapply are the passion I have for becoming a teacher in NYC and the fact that I am in a very unfulfilling job, which, not only saps my mind and spirit, but doesnt offer any benefits. I am reapplying because it has been my life long dream to stand in front of students as their teacher. I am a stronger candidate now because I have polished my skills, learned new ones, and I am more mature than I was just a year ago. I know I have so much untapped potential, and I am positive that I would be an asset to a school setting. Thank you for your time and consideration.

I enjoy my job and I get to help people at work on a regular basis; a lot of these people are on the field every day helping people themselves. I truly believe that I can take many principles that I presently apply and use them to help kids succeed in school.  I always consider other peoples perspective and I feel that Im at a point in my life where I can truly make a difference and use my strengths and help kids become good citizens.

I am reapplying because I really love the idea of teaching others, specially children. RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I have applied to be a New York City Teaching Fellow a few times, and with each year I have gotten more sure that becoming a fellow is my calling.   In most cases teachers don't want to work in high needs schools with children that may be troubled, but I do and I believe that given the right tools I would be able to make a difference in the lives of many.  I've watched all of the youtube videos from previous fellows, I've spoken to one about how passionate she is about her job, and I can see myself in those shoes.  I'm older, wiser, and more sure than ever that this is where I need to be in order to make a positive difference in education.

After receiving an offer to become a Fellow last spring, I spent countless hours carefully considering my next steps. I was confident I wanted to continue my career in the public schools, but I wanted to be sure. The moment I declined the offer, I started planning my reapplication. I spent my summer in New York City and fell in love with the city and the people. I returned home to Minnesota and signed up to work as a Reserve Teacher in Minneapolis Public Schools, an urban district facing challenges such as inconsistent leadership, racial disparities, and social unrest. Being a substitute teacher has been a humbling, eye-opening, and rewarding experience. I learn from every new classroom and school I enter and every new student I face. Even after the hardest of days, I know it is what I am meant to do. I am frustrated by the inequalities I see my students experiencing and my meager ability to make a difference or build relationships as a day-to-day sub. The time between my applications has been anything but a year off: I am more determined than ever to find my place in working towards equitable education for underprivileged urban students.
RRIssueLogTitle193: Complaint about Preparation for Lesson Planning
RRIssueLogBody194:
Received following email:

"Dear Fellows,

One of the ways I felt extremely unprepared to teach last fall was in the area of lesson planning. Yes, Fellows provided me with a general guideline of how to do it with general principles of what makes a good lesson. 

BUT. As an ENL teacher, I wish I would have started to incorporate Language Objectives into my lesson plans earlier. I didn't even learn about Language Objectives until an ENL colleague mentioned it at my school. If NYC DOE is going to be serious about meeting the needs of diverse learners, then we need to start addressing the needs of ELLs in a widespread, comprehensive way. What better place to start than Fellows? 

This should be the shared responsibility of Fellows AND University programs because this issue is extremely important. If Fellows is unable to incorporate Language Objectives into their current curriculum, then at least direct TADs, Coaches, and Instructional Leads to instruct the ENL teachers at their summer training site to start incorporating Language Objectives into their summer lesson plans. 

If this email gets beyond the first reader, please reach out with follow up questions or explanations. I know I am not alone in this.

Thanks!
Jen"

RRIssueLogBody3100:
"Good day,
I hope this email finds you well.  
On May 5, 2017 at 2:05pm a student stabbed and cut me with a scissor on my little finger of my left hand.  I went to the hospital.  I am traumatized and have a high level of anxiety.  I NEED HELP.  I cannot go back into that classroom.  The student's are traumatized, the paraprofessionals are traumatized and I am traumatized,  

This is an 8:1:1 class, 2-3 grades,  with four paraprofessionals in the room all standardized students. My AP has been using the Danielson framework as a punitive instrument to give me poor ratings.   I was not provided the curriculum for third grade testing students and I have four testing students.  I was given 1st and 2nd grade Go Math curriculum and one week before the spring break was given third grade Go Math workbooks.  I was told to create my own ELA curriculum, but was not provided with the third grade ELA curriculum work books, but was told to use Engage NY online, which I did.  I was not given any curriculum mapping for ELA or Math. And these children's state test scores are used for my MOSL ratings as well.  This is unfair and punitive.

I am not supported by my AP and she is not protecting me in the classroom.  She stated to me that I was being ""overly supported"" because I had a full time mentor on the job, who is also the Unit Coordinator, and because I was being sent to PD classes, which I thought we were supposed to receive. 

I have documented through anecdotal's how severe things are in this classroom.   I don't understand when all these things are this severe that she has not taken more actions to protect the teachers in the room.  I need your support in speaking with my AP and the Principal.  I am a first year teacher, and student and I have a student teacher in the room as well, with the most difficult class in the school.

These students are violent and aggressive.  They have injured my para by giving her two herniated discs.  I have two rotating sub paras in the room.  No sub has remained in the class.  And the student teacher is leaving at the end of the May, her student assignment is over.  Which leaves me with one permanent para, and she is the one who is and was injured by other student's in the room.  

The student that stabbed and cut me does not have a one to one paraprofessional and the administration is afraid of the mother.  I have one more informal observation, and I don't know how I can teach, when I can't go back into the classroom.  When I think about entering the room all I can see is the blood dripping from my hand and making a puddle on the floor. 

I am requesting your assistance for another placement, and for a placement with another population, preferable alternate assessment.  But I cannot do this without your help.  Would you please assist in speaking with my AP/Principal to move out of the school and out of this classroom.   I have been ill.  I contracted Bronchitis twice, from the student's and am suffering from it now and on medication.  I still go to school and do the best I can everyday.  This is not the population for me.  I need your help.

Thank you,
Jo Ann Cleghorne"

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I was motivated to reapply because, there is a student that needs to know they can achieve in spite of what society sees as a disability. Truly, I want to be an real-life example of the saying "if at first you don't succeed, try and try again".

I applied last year when I was working as a course coordinator at Columbia. I wanted to teach, but didn't have too much experience in it. This time around I've taught a session of a college level class and have been teaching high school students at Riverside Church. Now I know that this isn't a whim, this is a conscious choice to make a move toward a career that will make me feel fulfilled.

I received an email in mid November from the NYC Fellows asking for me to reconsider applying for the fellowship program. After consideration, I decided to reapply because I believe I can make an impact on students lives. I feel I will be a better prepared as a candidate this time having gone through the experience.

I firmly believe that one "No" should not  deter someone from what they are most passionate about. I am extremely passionate about educating children. I believe that I am a stronger candidate this time around because I have assessed all that  took place the first time I applied to New York City Teaching Fellows and have made some improvements on my approach.

I applied for the teaching fellows after discovering the program late. I submitted my application for an extended deadline, but shortly thereafter I was chosen to participate in a 'Selection Day' event. Although I wasn't chosen last year, I felt I was a strong candidate who would have a good chance to apply this year. This time around, I am more familiar with the application process and have considered the difficulties and benefits of becoming a fellow in depth. I spoke to other fellows about their experiences. I've spent time imagining myself as a teacher in the city instructing students with fewer resources and am excited to play that role. When I prepared for the 'Selection Day' last year, the opportunity to be a fellow was close, I felt excited about that possibility. I hope to achieve my goal this year.

I am intrinsically motivated. I was enthuse to reapply for this pivotal opportunity of making a valued contribution to nation building via this path of teaching. Generally, I am a strong believer that people must have the right attitude for all tasks at hand. For this reason, I am determined and committed to act only on important daily priorities and truly serve. I am confident that I have made the right decision and possess the attitude for the job at hand. Good decisions are made because they are RIGHT; hence, I reapplied.

I still see the NYC Teaching Fellowship as an opportunity to hone my pedagogical practice and affect positive change in students who are most in need. The difference between myself as an applicant last year and this year is my enhanced sense of leadership. Over the summer, I participated in a Leadership conference focused on sustainability, which emphasized the importance of creating sustainable practices that foster empowerment and achievement. On a similar note, the English graduate department at my University asked me to take a leadership role as the Interim Graduate Secretary, administratively facilitating pedagogical interventions and student learning. Becoming a more leadership-oriented candidate, I believe, will contribute to my success in the classroom.

I am reapplying because I'm determined to support students coming from low-income communities. After I experienced the application process with NYC Teaching Fellows, I knew that this was something I want to be apart of. I learned new teaching methods during my interview process, and I am a stronger candidate since I last applied because I'm eager to learn more! Teaching Fellows would be a great learning experience for me as well as an outlet to show students with special needs how to maximize their potential.

I am reapplying because I feel the urge to make a difference in the world of education. Since I last applied, I finished an internship in a special-needs classroom and also worked with a sizable amount of kids during this past summer. Though these experiences were wrought with difficulties and nerve-wracking moments, the positive end results affirmed my continual desire to work with children. I cannot describe what I felt every time one of my students learned how to ride a bicycle on their own. I was even happier to discover that all 8 of my students from my internship had advanced to the next grade level. I now believe that Im a stronger candidate because I am more confident in my abilities to spark positive change from my students. Whatever their situation is, whether they come from low-income households or whether they simply want someone to listen to them and give them attention, I realized that I could make a real difference in their lives by being present and teaching them more things in the hopes that they develop into well-rounded people.
the last time i applied, i wasn't what category i was qualified to teach in. Now with a bit of research i am reapplying in a different field.

RRIssueLogBody194:
According to Dan Stuckart, Fellow sent an email to new Lehman College president. Fellow confided in English Advisor that he had been homeless before. He has made bad choices. 

From: Jos Luis Cruz 
Sent: Wednesday, August 17, 2016 8:39 AM
To: LUZ JIMENEZ <LUZ.JIMENEZ@lehman.cuny.edu>
Subject: Aaron Hunt
 
Aaron Hunt
in the last week
 This has to be the worst administrative support I have ever encountered in my entire life and as a result of the ineptitude of the financial aid department and it's staff, I have been homeless in the two months I have been enrolled at Lehman despite being qualified and approved for over $20,000 worth of federal loans. The problem? You have to pry it out of their evil iron fists first. I can't begin to tell you how depressed and destitute I have been since I was FORCED to go to this school. My program put me at this laughing stock of an educational institute. The only thing I have learned since I've been here is how to survive on the streets. Time is running out and so is what little money I have left... DO NOT GO TO THIS SCHOOL!!!! I cannot emphasize how dangerous it is to be done the way that I have. HEED MY WARNING. I am STUCK and CANNOT leave even if I wanted to. DO NOT GO TO THIS SCHOOL!!!
--
Jos Luis Cruz, Ph.D.
President, Lehman College
The City University of New York
 


From: Aaron Hunt <adhx.mail@gmail.com>
Date: Sunday, August 14, 2016 5:34 AM
To: "PEDRO.BAEZ" <PEDRO.BAEZ@lehman.cuny.edu>, "KALYA.CASTILLO" <KALYA.CASTILLO@lehman.cuny.edu>, "JOHN.HOLLOWAY" <JOHN.HOLLOWAY@lehman.cuny.edu>, "SABRINA.RAMSUNDAR@lc.cuny.edu" <SABRINA.RAMSUNDAR@lc.cuny.edu>, "JERILYN.DAY" <JERILYN.DAY@lehman.cuny.edu>, "financial.aid@mail.lehman.edu" <financial.aid@mail.lehman.edu>, Daniel <daniel.stuckart@lehman.cuny.edu>
Subject: Letter of Distress (PLEASE READ)

To those who have the power to make a difference,


My name is Aaron D. Hunt (EMPLID: 23577897). Im a graduate student who recently moved here to participate in the NYC Teaching Fellows program. As a part of the program, I was assigned to Lehman College. Prior to my arrival, I made numerous attempts to secure direct loans from the financial aid department to supplement the cost of school materials (such as books) not covered by the DOE as well as living expensesconsidering the fact that as a born and bred Southerner struggling to keep myself afloat during my undergrad program, the cost of living was considerably cheaper and the wages were meager in comparison. However, since I began the process for securing financial aid for the Summer 2016 semester, I have ran into a considerable degree of obstruction, setbacks from both the NYC Teaching Fellows and Lehman, and ultimately, Lehman itself. While there were administrators who were able to support me marginallyjust enough to keep me sheltered throughout most of the Pre-Service Training part of NYCTF and Summer courses facilitated by Lehmanthe appropriation of financial aid has been delayed so much that now I am in a circumstance where I can no longer provide for myself the most basic human dignities: food, water, and shelter. Because I applied for aid for Summer and Fall of 2016, I was under the impression following several meetings with Mr. Hill, the financial aid director, that I would be provided aid for those semesters pending approval. It hurt me deeply to see that aid was deferred instead to the Fall 2016 and Spring 2017 semestersone of which I never requested, because I knew that I would be in a better economic condition to not have to borrow anything to cover the cost of both course materials and living arrangements. While I have been fortunate enough to be appointed a position as a teacher at Mott Hall V High School for this upcoming school year, it does not mitigate the immediate perils that I face at this time. I am without income for the next two monthsthe rest of August and September, and will not receive my first paycheck as a teacher until October. So it is dispiriting and gravely concerning that in light of the extremes that surround my condition. At this time, I am sleeping on trains (day and night), facing the threat of eviction from a storage facility that I need so desperately so that my stuff isnt all over the place, while having to contend with a dangerous climatic flux. This entire weekend I have endured consecutive days of 100+ degree heat indexes that have caused me to periodically experience the affects of heat exhaustion: I have awakened on trains dizzy with headaches, nausea, sleep deprivation, confusion, dehydration, and without the ability to use the bathroom when I need to. 

This is no way to treat someone who has consistently shown dedication and faith in the institutions that provide him with the opportunities to make beneficial contributions to teaching and the social, emotional, and cognitive development of adolescents in the classroom. I have been waiting so patiently and have been so gracious in spite of the diminutive affects of what support has been given toward mitigating the deplorable condition I have experienced. Please, with all of my substance, I implore of those who have the power to change the outcome of my current situation to please do all that you can now to do what is right and to bestow me the aid that I so desperately fought for specifically for this turbulent time in my lifewhen I need it most. I am hungry now. I am thirsty now. I am tired and sleep deprived now. I am depressed and morally degraded now.Not three weeks from now. Not when everyone gets back from their vacations. I havent had a reprieve from my adversities in over two years. I feel as though these mishaps have been so consistent and so repetitive that it is hard not to feel as though the difficulties Ive experienced have not been deliberate. Please help me. I am running out of time and money. I cannot afford to go two months without a place to sleep, food to eat, and water to drink and I dont deserve any of this considering how hard I workedthe things I have gone through in my life up to this point, graduating with honors, and working hard to earn those better opportunitiesjust to avoid something like this. Please help me. Financial aid is supposed to be approved for the Summer and Fall of 2016. Spring 2017 aid was neither requested nor authorized per the application I submitted. Mishaps like this is what has caused this situation to be prolonged and worsen. Please reach out to me as soon as possible.


Sincerely,

Aaron D. Hunt
Teaching Fellow; English 7-12
NYC Teaching Fellows
adhx.mail@gmail.com
347-225-3987

I called Alexandra today to speak about her attendance. I reminded her that she has used all of her emergency absences and must be present for the remainder of training. She stated that she was aware that she used all of her absences and that she will be present for the remainder of training. I reiterated the importance of attendance, and she said she understood.

"Hello,

My name is Matthew Martin. I was assigned to attend St. John's University. Since I was assigned this university, my schedule has been changed three times by our liaison, Professor Anthony Napoli . Today, I attended my first class only to be told that my name did not appear on the class roll. Professor Napoli arrived at the classroom to tell the instructor that, in fact I WAS registered for this class and that I should remain seated. I stayed for the entire class. However, when I arrived home and was at last able to access the St. John's student site (MyStJohns)--for which we were only given instructions today--I discovered that I was registered for an entirely different class. I am now scrambling to contact my instructors and Professor Napoli to determine what is happening and how to make up my assignments. 

The above situation did not only happen to me. Today during orientation I witnessed SPED Math students being told that they were supposed to attend orientation and classes this morning rather than the afternoon. When they protested that the email schedule they'd received from Professor Napoli read that the time/place to meet indicated they should arrive in the afternoon, he waved away their concerns.

My experience with St. John's thus far has been very stressful. I understand that the Teaching Fellows is limited in what they can do in this situation, however, I am very concerned about my future, and that of my fellow Fellows, at this university going forward. Please be aware that there is a great deal of confusion at St. John's at the moment and I am not confident that it can be rectified.

best, Matthew Martin"

From: Singleton Ebony (32K564) 
Sent: Monday, January 30, 2017 5:38 PM
To: Choe Nuree <NChoe@schools.nyc.gov>
Cc: Gonzalez Llermi <LGonzal20@schools.nyc.gov>; Touray Tutti (32K564) <TTouray@schools.nyc.gov>
Subject: Professional Summary for Teaching Fellow Mariano Lloret
Importance: High

Good Afternoon, Ms. Choe,

Thank you for taking my call this afternoon. 
Below is the summary you requested regarding, Teacher, Mariano Lloret. Please let me know if you need additional information. 

Measure of Teacher Practice
Currently, under the teacher evaluation, Mariano 's overall rating is an ineffective. He demonstrates lack of growth in regards unit and lesson planning, in particularly, content knowledge and pedagogy. He has also failed to show progress in regards to engaging students in learning, using assessments in instruction and questioning and discussion techniques. 

In addition to his preparation time, Mariano is given an addition period a day to meet with his mentor daily to plan his unit and lesson plans and receive feedback. He is scheduled to receive feedback on his unit plans from the principal and assistant principal. He has missed these meetings or comes unprepared.

After each observation, in-person meetings are held with Mariano to give him specific feedback to further his instructional practices. None of the feedback suggestion has been implemented.

Special Education Caseload and IEP Completion
To date, Mariano, has completed one tri-annual and no annual reviews from the 16 students assigned to his caseload. Mr. Lloret, has received internal and external professional development surrounding IEP writing. In addition, IEP writing templates and exemplars have been shared to support his writing deficiencies. Unfortunately, none of the supports or resources has resulted in the completion of his assigned IEPs. Student IEPs remained out of compliance, until we switched his caseload to the IEP Coordinator for immediate completion.

Attendance Summary
Mariano had 7 absences within the first 4 months of school;
4 of the 7 absences resulted in an extended weekend (Friday and/or Monday);
3 of the 7 medical documentation was provided ;
Mariano was also late 3 times and was observed leaving early without permission which resulted in a letter to file.

Disciplinary Letters
Thus far, Mariano has received four disciplinary letters to file:

October 20th for failure to have a lesson plan; 
November 7th for not having a bulletin board after given an extension of over a month; 
November 7th for leaving work roughly 30 minutes before his contractual time on October 26, 2016;
January 25th for excessive absences.


Best Regards,
Ebony N. Singleton
Assistant Principal
---
Bushwick Community High School (32K564)
231 Palmetto Street 3rd Floor, Brooklyn, NY
Ph: 718.443.3083 Ext. 336
Fax: 718.919.0781

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
My 2010 application was half-hearted at best. Ill be honest. I was only about two years out of college and was desperate to get out of a mediocre job. I had teaching experience abroad, so I told myself that I might as well apply.

Five years later, its quite a different story. I am now earning a huge salary and have been expatriated abroad until Spring 2016 by my company  hardly mediocre, and quite fortunate I know. I feel Ive grown quite a bit professionally and as a person since my last application. Five more years of life experience and five more years of business success must surely make me a stronger candidate.

The other difference is that I am not simply looking for a way out of my current job. I am much more intent on making an honest career change this time around. Ive been researching masters degrees and reading all sorts of teaching blogs. In fact, if I dont succeed in my application this time, I plan on enrolling at Teachers College in the fall. Because, as I stated previously, I no longer feel that I can consciously work in a for-profit industry. I want to directly contribute to society in a positive way. There is no better way than teaching. 

Another influence since my last application has been the many friends Ive made who are NYC teachers, including a math fellow in this very program. While all of my teacher friends arent shy about saying its demanding, hard work, they are also visibly much happier than my private sector friends. And theyve all encouraged me to pursue this dream.

The last motivating factor was the passing of my grandmother, who was a teacher for 35 years. It took her passing for me to realize what a noble profession teaching really is. I know thats probably clich by now, but its a selfless and undervalued profession. It requires complete devotion and commitment. The way people spoke of my grandmothers passion for her classroom really reminded me of that. Id love the chance to follow in her footsteps. So, Im very glad my journey over the last five years has led me right back here to her and to this program.

RRIssueLogBody194:
Megan was observed this morning. The lesson was rated a 1 - pre-novice across all indicators. Afterwards, Megan engaged in a feedback conversation with Kerianne Harrison and myself. The following is a summary of that conversation:

- I advised Megan that her glow was the use of familiar commercials to engage her students. Her grow was in classroom culture, specifically around transitions and student idle time. 
- I advised Megan that the lesson observed was rated at pre-novice across all indicators. Referring back to low inference notes, the greatest concerns were with how she 1) supervised the transition from circle to group tables, 2) idle time, especially for the yellow group. Specifically, that the transition should have been announced after both videos (i.e., direct instruction).
- Transition between circle and group table - Megan had set up a system  of color coding in which students were expected to match the circle on their card to the circle on their group table. When Megan announced the transition, two students moved to their table right away. Another two to three students moved about 1 minute later. 
- Although the yellow group was already at their group location (which is also their circle location), they waited for their materials for about 4 minutes.

- I modeled how to execute a transition with a student, to show Megan how a paraprofessional may provide support for a student during transition.  

- We (Megan, Kerianne, and I) discussed possible strategies for Megan to use to ameliorate these issues. Specifically, Megan was advised to use more explicit What To Do directions in supervising the transition. Kerianne gave her three explicit directions: stand up, walk to table, match your color.  Megan then practiced implementing these instructions. 
- Kerianne advised Megan to create a visual for students (for the SmartBoard) and staff that delineate the groups by color. Megan was advised that she could use student names as well as their pictures.
- We asked Megan how she usually communicates her expectations to the paraprofessionals for student behavior and academics. Megan stated that she usually just speaks to them about this. I suggested using index cards with explicit instructions to communicate with paraprofessionals about her expectations for student supports. Megan stated that she was hesitant about giving index cards to paraprofessionals because the students may get hold of them and rip them apart. I asked her to try to do it anyway. That if she gave the paraprofessionals the index cards, it is unlikely that the students would take them and rip them apart.

- Kerianne advised Megan to create a powerpoint with student groupings and assigned paraprofessionals as a visual for the transition between the circle (direct instruction) and group work.

Student Idleness
- We also discussed the fact that the yellow group waited 4 minutes to get their materials. At first, Megan said that she did not think it took that long for the group to get their materials. Later she explained that the group did not receive their materials right away because she was circulating among the other two groups. I advised her that she could have dropped their materials off first, then go to the other tables (which already had the student materials on them). Megan said that she did not do this because of the tendency of the students in the yellow group to tear up and eat materials.
- We also spoke about the expectations for students who were not being engaged by Megan directly during circle time. Specifically, that these students should be engaged by the paraprofessionals when they are not being directly questioned by her. 

We reviewed Megan's glow and grow and next steps. Megan stated that her next steps are to 1) provide specific What To Do directions for students and 2) address student idleness by providing materials up front and communicating her expectations to paraprofessionals via index cards.

Megan said that she will create a visual with groupings for the Smartboard. To address the student idleness, Megan agreed to provide materials to the yellow group before checking in with the other two groups.

Maria called to express frustration and concern about not yet being hired for a position. She opened with "Good Morning New York City Teaching Fellows, still don't have a job and calling back because you all never respond to me," in a sing song sarcastic tone. Maria is nervous that she will not find a position by the start of the school year and felt it was unjust that the position she had secured in an isolated classroom was not granted as it doesn't meet our hiring criteria. She said she felt "strong-armed by the Fellows who have been no help at all to take a position in the Bronx and that would be a 3 hour commute for her." I shared that we were not trying to do that and our aim as a program was to ensure Fellows had vacancy lists, hiring fairs, resume workshops and office hours next week to help Fellows find positions. She asked if those office hours meetings would involve our program, "calling up principals on my behalf to ensure I get a job." She became emotional and shared that her anxiety came from a place of wanting to have a job to support her family. I shared that I understood it is a stressful time and mentioned that many principals may have been out last week but will be in the office on Monday so it may be worth following up with emails to ensure that your message is at the top of their inbox when they return. She asked me "do you think it's better that I don't have a job than if I have a job that doesn't quite meet the criteria of your program?"
