Summary
Fred received a NFA in teaching sample planning form. Candidate did not use the lesson plan template. Fred uploaded a word document with definitions and a list of steps to ratify the Constitution. Teacher and student interactions are not listed. There is significant misunderstanding of how to use the form. Lesson also does not contain a CFU.

Fred received a FA in CA and a FA- in CD. He stated the definitions and steps of ratification for the US constitution. He repeated himself a few times so students could copy notes. He did not ask a CFU beyond having students read the notes from the board. He talks about content but does model it. He did not provide examples or use a model to help students make sense of the information. Fred received a FA in MIT. He used his time wisely and recapped the lesson midpoint and at the end. For ES, he received a FA-. He had minimal interactions with participants. He called on 3 out of 6 students and asked them to copy notes. He also lectured for more than half of the lesson. 

In the initial direction during the GA, Fred did not use all components of WTD. He used sequential; however, he was missing specific/ concrete and observable. He applied feedback from colleagues and as a result, his revised direction was correct. He gave feedback to 1 out of 2 partners during the WTD. In the reteach, Fred used WTD correctly one time during the lesson, and missed other opportunities to include it in his lesson. He received a FA in CT for GA and RT. Overall, he received a NFA in CT because of the TSPF.

I would like Fred's application to be reviewed. He is severely visually impaired and this disability affected his performance. There were barriers to his learning without access. For example, he had trouble using the planning form online because of his sight. There was not a modification for him to succeed therefore, he created his own form. Also, he struggled during the group activity because he could not fully read the poster or the handout. He had a magnified glass; however, the pace of the group activity prevented him to fully participate. He was very verbal and participated as best he could. I surmise that the lack of modification for the worksheet accounted for his low rating in TSPF and GA. 

According to the rubric, Fred is a select out candidate because of NFA in CT.

RRIssueLogBody5106:
Staceyann called my personal cell around 8pm this evening and left a message asking for my advice about attending a D75 tour she registered for tomorrow morning.  She mentioned she would have to wake up at 4 AM in order to attend and wanted to know if I knew about parking options near the school.  She didn't want to cancel without my advice. She asked me to call or text her back. She had access to my cell phone number because I provided it in an email to all registered Fellows in the event of an emergency.  Below is my email response to her.

Hi Staceyann,

I received your voicemail message. Please note that my personal cell number was provided to Fellows in the event of emergencies on the morning of the tours. For all future inquiries, you should reach out via phone or email to the NYC Teaching Fellows office.

I have not been to the District 75 school we are scheduled to tour tomorrow so I cannot personally speak to parking options. If you choose to attend the tour, I recommend you utilize Google Maps to identify nearby parking lots since I doubt the school has a lot (it is located in the East Village).

Given the intense commute you referenced in your message, I understand if you opt not to come and appreciate you letting me know your final decision before 8 AM tomorrow (via email).

Staceyann, please be aware that Pre-Service Training will require you to be in various places in NYC very early in the morning and you'll have coursework to attend until early evenings.  If commuting into the city is an issue for an 8 AM tour, you may want to consider alternate transportation or lodging options for the summer to make for an easier commute to your school and University.

Thanks,
 
Allison Lavey
Program Manager, Early Career Success
Office of Teacher Recruitment & Quality
New York City Department of Education
65 Court Street, Room 321 | BK, NY 11201
718.935.4238

RRIssueLogBody194:
Joseph called in wanted to discuss being places on a Performance Improvement Plan. He called our office and spoke with me first, I then transferred the call to Meha. After his conversation with Meha, Anna followed up with him. 

- Joseph doesn't understand why he was placed on a PIP, he feels he has performed well throughout all of PST so far. He says that all of the staff at his TA have expressed he has performed very well previously and don't know what happened during his observation. 
- He doesn't understand why only one formal observation is taken into account and we can't consider all of is informal observations for this evaluation "Why am I being punished for 15 minutes when I've performed very well for 100+ other hours"
- When explained that a PIP is meant as a support for Fellows and not meant to be punitive - he doesn't agree with that and feels like it is a punishment.
- By the end of my conversation with him before transferring him to Meha, he still wanted to protest being on a PIP even after explaining that he is not able to. 
- Throughout the conversation Joseph repeatedly interrupted and would talk simultaneously.
RRIssueLogBody297:
I called Joseph to follow up on his call with Meha, as he wished to speak with someone else.

Joseph was concerned that he was placed on a PIP based on his formal observation ratings, given that he feels he has performed well in his informal observations and given his performance in the non-anchor techniques. I explained our process, referred him to the PST Handbook for more context, and reiterated that PIP is not punitive but is a support to ensure that he is able to work with his Coach on his development areas to ensure he is successful during training this summer.

Joseph clarified next steps for performance moving forward, and we discussed how he can work with his Coach to improve in the anchor techniques, non-anchor techniques, and in observations using the Instructional Framework.

Joseph was concerned about the impact of the Performance Improvement Plan on his ability to be hired - I clarified the timeline on which the vast majority of Fellows are hired (early August, after PST), He also questioned how many people who receive the support of a PIP ultimately successfully complete PST - I shared the context that is shared in our Fellow materials, that the majority of Fellows on PIPs, through focused work and growth and development with their coaches, go on to successfully complete PST.

Joseph let me know multiple times during the call that I am very well trained, and that I can tell my boss that I am very well trained, and that he would have trained me the same way when he was working in the corporate world.

Joseph asked if he could show up on Wednesdays and do nothing, since he is not being observed on those days. I clarified that he is still responsible for his students' academic development on Wednesdays, and responsible for working at all times to develop and grow as a teacher, even if he is not being formally observed. 

Joseph asked if there is an appeals process, and I let him know that there is not an appeals process.
RRIssueLogBody3100:
Meha spoke with this Fellow about his Performance Improvement Plan. Notes from her call are below.

- Joseph Prisco comes from the corporate world, and doesnt feel like, in his past experience, performance has been based off of 1 observation. Meha explained the multiple measures approach to him, but he is ultimately upset that he is on a PIP based on one 15 minute observation.
- Concurrently, he claims that the staff at his site (TADs, his coaches), think he is performing really well, and also dont understand why he is on a PIP  they just did it because they had to.
- He also says that the observation that contributed to his PIP was on a day where he threw his back out. Part of what hurt his score was about idle time, and missing instruction, which he attributes to his back injury
- Ultimately, he wants his informal observations to be taken into account, not just the two formal ones, since this would be more equitable from his perspective and capture his overall performance
- Lastly, he was told that he would have to wait till decisions to go back in the job pool. Meha clarified this, but he still doesnt feel OK about the implications of a PIP on his job search.

Hi Marian, 

That's great that the principal is hiring her for the coming school year - great news! Is this a D75 school? Because she's a Fellow who was selected specifically for D75, she must secure a position for the next school year at a D75 school. The Fellow must speak to her university coordinator about this position to see if she can take this job since I'm assuming this wasn't a D75 school. 

Additionally, principals cannot hire Fellows for the summer, as they are assigned to summer school by the Fellows program. We call the summer schools Training Academies and my colleagues have spent many long hours cultivating relationships with schools to establish our Training Academies, where Fellows are assigned in large groups where they are supported by our Summer Fellows program staff (Coaches, Training Academy Directors, and NYCTF skills-building session instructors). 

Please let me know if you have any additional questions!

Best,
Nuree

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
The factors that motivated me to reapply is the continuous dire education circumstances in low income communities and my continuous desire to live a purpose driven life.

Ive become a stronger candidate for the fellowship position because Ive experience an increase in valuable life experience and accomplishments. 

Since my last application to the fellowship program, I and my wife have welcomed a daughter into this world, who is currently four years old. Ive enrolled my daughter in swimming lessons, dance class, French lessons and regularly take her to the museums. By presenting these activities to my daughter, Ive witnessed her cognitive development and learned that once a child feels safe and happy, they are fully receptive to innovative learning, creative ideas and complex information. 

Ive also had the opportunity to volunteer as a teacher with the Citizen School organization, which partners with public middle schools in low income communities. The experience was very exciting because I managed to recruit an individual from the advertising professional to assist me with teaching the class. We presented the advertising education to the children and experienced them being receptive and creating their own advertising ad. There were instances where some of the class participants were disruptive and we learned to approach them in an empathetic manner to resolve the disruption. Our teaching motto was keep it fresh, and entertaining and we rewarded positive behaviors by surprising the children with pizza pies and snacks.

I had the pleasure of working for the largest and most prestigious museum in the world, which is the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The Museum was a hub of creativity and wealth of artistic knowledge.  Having direct access to the education, special events and Curatorial department of the museum enabled me to be creative and think outside the box. The education department created a variety of programs to engage toddlers and teens to be early and regular patrons to the museum. Educational programs such as Art Explores, which are tours covering a wealth of art topics for students between the ages of 11 to14; and Family programs which offered story time reading and classes for toddlers. Experiencing and witnessing the success of these programs, through a high participation rate and seeing the excitement of the children, was another confirmation on how receptive children are to creative and innovative ways of learning.

All of my experience from parenthood, volunteering as a teacher and working in a hub of creativity has further heighten the perspective that a child is capable of learning anything and everything if they are provided with an environment where they feel safe and free to inquire and express themselves. As a result of my experience, I will approach teaching with a renewed creative point of view that is empathetic towards the students to engage them in learning.

RRIssueLogTitle193: Arabic Language Certificate for ESL Eligibility
RRIssueLogBody194:
"Marie,

I am writing in response to an email you sent me earlier today about additional materials needed to determine my ESL eligibility. I have pasted your original email below as a reference. 

As for the information you are looking for, it is a bit complicated so allow me to explain:

As you noted from my transcript, I took 11 credits of Arabic in college at the University of New England. The courses were taught every year by a different Fulbright scholar and only Arabic I was offered. I was not satisfied with that so every new semester, I convinced the professor to do an Arabic independent study with me so I could further my learning. 

After Arabic III, I decided I wanted to continue studying Arabic post-graduation. I applied to the American University in Cairo as well as Middlebury College's Arabic Language program. I was accepted to both but chose to attend AUC's Arabic Language Intensive Program in Egypt for a more immersive experience. The trouble was that because of a technicality and because it would take place in the months after graduation, I wouldn't get credit for the courses unless I signed on to pay a full semester's tuition to both universities. The Dean at UNE, however, wanted to help me so he agreed to have it count toward my Arabic III class by way of a ""Study Abroad Experience."" It is listed on my transcript as such (SAB - Summer Semester 2010) but doesn't adequately connect the two.

This gets more complicated because I had asked for an official copy of my certificate when I arrived back in the United States. That was around the same time the revolution broke out in 2010. As you can imagine, the postal service there was not functioning as we would have liked and I never received it. I have requested it a number of times since but other problems have come up on their end (they need a certain kind of credit card or need someone in Cairo to actually pick it up for me).

I can and will try again to see what I can have them send me electronically as soon as possible but it's proved futile in the past. I can also have a professor at the University of New England who signed off as my study abroad liaison write some kind of confirmation that I was enrolled and successfully completed the program.

As for the program, I took 20+ hours of classes a week while I was there in June and July of 2010. Classes were in Modern Standard Arabic (MSA) and colloquial Egyptian. I also took cultural classes on things like Islam. Below you'll find a link that further explains the summer program I was involved in.

I hope I have adequately explained this unusual situation. I'm also uploading a copy of this correspondence and any other materials I can think of that would help to Teacher Track to help streamline this process. I'm more than happy to provide any additional information you'll need and I certainly hope this doesn't hurt but rather helps my application!

Thank you so much for all your time and efforts and I hope I have the pleasure of working with you in future.

Marissa Simoes


http://schools.aucegypt.edu/academics/ALI/ALIN/SummerProgram/Pages/default.aspx

Original email from Marie:
Hi Marisa,

Thank you for checking in! We wanted to do a last verification of your coursework for your ESL eligibility. We see that, in addition to your 11 Arabic credits, you also received an Arabic Language Certificate. Can you please provide more information regarding this certificate so we can have it on file? Was this certificate accepted for college credit?

Please submit your response via the Contact Form.

Kindly,
Marie
 "

RRIssueLogBody194:
Have had several calls with New Visions and Hunter re: candidate and ability for DOE and NV to potentially be able to meet accommodation needs. Candidate is nonverbal and would need ASL interpretation. 

Spoke with the Accommodations Coordinator within the DOE, who provided some suggestions but wasn't able to provide a definitive answer of what exactly would be the accommodations because she would need to submit an Accommodations Request form with medical documentations to determine that. He shared that D75 is often very supportive of meeting teacher accommodations. 

In my phone call with NV and Hunter this morning, Hunter is able to provide interpretative needs for coursework but it would be up to DOE and NV to provide during summer school and other training sessions, as well as when she is teaching during the school year. NV suggested a hybrid way to support this candidate if accepted and enrolled - enroll her as a D75 Fellow at Hunter and have her take courses with Chem UTR residents - so that she can work in a D75 school and still be earning her certification in Chemistry. 

Spoke with Erika and moving forward with NV's proposed hybrid model would be too complex. 
(1) Hunter does not have a D75 7-12 cohort, only a 1-6 group. 
(2) She can only be in one program. This hybrid model would be too complicated and would involved too many staff resources and adjustments to both programs to meet the needs of one Fellow. 

Hunter will be following up with their folks. There is a call scheduled for Friday, 5/6, to touch base with Hunter and NV.

When I applied over a decade ago, I had little school experience. While I felt the call to teach, I admit I held an over-idealizedeven naiveview of teaching. Since then, I have taken increasing responsibility in the classroom: tutoring small groups and after-school clubs, assisting teachers, co-teaching and finally becoming a non-certified temporary teacher (and interim head of department) for one term. Now, after considerable time spent in different schools (including low-income London public schools), I feel more grounded in reality, more experienced and consequently more resolved and skilled to enter the classroom and start making a difference. 

The meaningful relationships I developed with young people have emboldened my determination to become a teacher. It was a privilege to spend time with (low-income) youth in inner-city London schools and to research and apply ways of raising their achievement. Additionally, I have since earned an MA with the highest grades of my cohort, adding successful graduate school experience to my classroom experiences. Finally, having lived in Europe (Spain and England) for a decade since applying to the Fellows, I have gained a greater understanding of different cultures and of the urgent societal value of investing in quality public education. At 39, I am a seasoned individual, a reflective practitioner and a career changer with a solid professional background and valuable transferable skills. My diverse approximations into the classroom provide continuous evidence of a profound desire to become a teacher in order to to help learners achieve and excel.

RRIssueLogBody194: Family circumstances
withdrawing from program, wishes to re-apply next year

I spoke with Richard today when he came into the NYCTF office to discuss his outplacement decision. I let him know that I was happy to answer questions, but that the decision had been carefully considered by a team of people and there is no appeals process.

He asked a couple of questions about how his overall score is calculated, so I shared his final average scores, explained how to calculate the overall score, and referred him to the appropriate pages of the PST handbook where this is explained.

He also mentioned that he didn't realize he was struggling as much as he was, since his Coach gave him positive feedback on his improvement in classroom management, so we discussed his PIP and how that was a strong indication that he needed to improve in his classroom observations.

He is interested in pursuing another pathway to teaching, so we discussed why he is not eligible for the NYCTC, the fact that any future coursework at Relay won't be covered by NYCTF, and how to use the Spark Opportunity website to explore other pathways to teaching. He asked about teaching on a long-term sub license in the fall, and i explained that that's only an option for Fellows who are currently enrolled in the program. 

He asked if he could speak to his principal about teachign in the fall, and I explained that he will need to be certified or on a Trans B to teach in the fall so this wouldn't be possible.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: Since I last applied, I overcame few professional challenges that corroborates the confidence I have on my abilities and the positive attitude I possess during challenging situations. As a bilingual teacher assistant, I found myself in one classroom without a leading classroom teacher for three months and at another classroom for one month.  Despite the unexpected events, I and the monolingual teacher assistant courageously faced all classroom's responsibilities; delivering lesson planning activities, setting up classroom according to UPK model, updating bulletin boards, conducting students' assessments and observations, tracking student's IEP's goals, conducting parent teachers conference, routinely busing, meals, school trips etc. Besides the above challenges, we encountered challenges at the school due to lack of resources.  However, we relied on our ingenuity, determination, and team-work to bring the best of ourselves to achieve the best in our students. We utilized the resources available to create activities that were part of the lesson plan and still met the academic standards. The students were able to graduate and continue their successful path towards kindergarten. The sense of accomplishment I felt at the end of the year is indescribable. I witnessed and experienced the different types of struggles that characterizes low income schools and its population.  Therefore, I strongly believe that I am more equipped, confident,  passionate, and dedicated than last year as I have convinced myself that success is measure by progress not by perfection.

I believe I am a stronger candidate since I last applied because of my further insight and research into successful strategies for teaching special needs children, as well as further research on autism in the classroom.  Importantly, by spending time with my niece I have experienced, first-hand, how a positive influence can change a childs life.  I believe that experience can translate itself into having the same benefits for special needs students.  Of note, I have expressed my desire to become a special needs teacher to my long-time employer, Dennis OSullivan, Esq., and he has expressed his whole-hearted support in my endeavor.  My prior application was one of 400 considered for interview among 11,000 applications.  To the extent that I formerly merited consideration to be interviewed, and my fervent desire and commitment to serve as a teacher, I believe I can make a decisive contribution to the New York City Teaching Fellows as a special needs teacher.

When I received the email that I would not be accepted into the program last spring of 2015, I decided to look for another outlet to be able to achieve my goal of getting accepted into the New York City Teaching Fellows Program.  I applied to Teacher's College Columbia University to get my TESOL Certificate and was accepted into the summer program. It was an intensive few months and I learned so much and managed to get a job teaching ESOL to adults with the New York Public Library. I teach one class in the Bronx and another in Washington Heights. Most of the students are immigrants and really want to be there to learn. This process has made me a more confident, able, and experienced candidate for the New York City Teaching Fellows.

Last year I was uncertain that the New York City Teaching Fellows was the correct path for me to pursue in my career as an educator. My application reflected this.

Over the past year, I have given much thought to determine the next step in my career. I found out that a dear friends sister is a Fellow. She teaches 7th grade special education at PS 687 and is aunt to a child with special needs. I have observed her classroom and we have had extensive discussions about the challenges her students face coming from an underserved community, and the skills and techniques she has learned through the Fellows, mentors, and colleagues.
  
Every single one of her students has been personally affected by gun violence. This reminded me of my days as a substitute teacher at the High School for Graphic Communication Arts. I was teaching mathematics to a vulnerable student population with no training and no textbooks. I supplied pencils and paper. As much as I loved working at HSGCA I wish I had the tool box of skills the Fellows provides. I would have been a far more effective teacher. 

The former head of high school of my alma mater, who retired last year as principal of the George Jackson Academy, a school that attracts its student population from low-income families, suggested the New York City Teaching Fellows as a pathway I would be interested in. He is familiar with my work, professional and volunteer, and of my interest to continue to work with low income, at-risk youth. 

The average IQ for students at GJA is 131. GJA has provided some incredible opportunities for a minuscule fraction of New York Citys at-risk students. This brings up a very important question - have we given up on the students with average IQs? What about those with special needs? No, I havent, and neither have the members of the Teaching Fellows.

Here I find myself mid-career and I aspire to do something meaningful that goes further than volunteer work. I truly believe that the Teaching Fellows is the right place for me to pursue my dreams and benefit the future of New York Citys student population, our future.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I applied to the Fellows in 2011. I am better candidate now because of one word: wisdom.

For the past three years I have worked in a high-needs school in Jamaica, Queens, as a paraprofessional. I'm a different person because of people like Ms. Rock, a teacher whom I served under. 

When I came to Ms. Rock's class every day to work, I knew that she would not  tolerate a lackadaisical effort. I thought of this when I ran the hills in Forest Park before work. There's no "B" game when you serve in her class. Now, I shoot for peak performance every day.

I'm a better candidate because during the summer of 2013 I did something I was petrified of: I got on a plane to take a trip to El Salvador. Prior to that, I had not taken an out-of-country trip since 2007, to Mexico. I had a nightmare experience on that trip. But I summoned the will to get up that morning and get on that plane. It changed my life. 

Since facing that fear, I have traveled to Peru, Colombia and Mexico many times over. I've enrolled in a Spanish language class, because the whole world speaks at least two languages. I've been robbed at knife point for my phone. I've seen people selling Chiclets on the street in order to eat. I've had people open their homes to me when I was in need. 

When I was in Bacalar, Mexico, in April, I saw a man wandering the streets. He was a young man, perhaps 28 years old, dressed in rags. He motioned with his hands furiously in front of his face.

It struck me that this man was autistic. I watched as he sidled up next to a vendor selling tamales from a stand. He tapped her, lightly, on the back. Then he danced away. He was hungry, but he could not express it.

"Why is that man doing that?," I asked a woman on the street.

"Something is wrong with his head," she answered in Spanish.

At that moment, I saw the need that Mexico- that the whole world has- in addressing this population.

RRIssueLogTitle296: Follow-up to outplacement convo from TAD
RRIssueLogBody297:
Hi Carly,


I'd be happy to provide some context for that conversation. A coach did accidentally reply all to an email that Chad was on.  He had given her a great deal of push-back during her feedback conversation, so Sean and I had both stepped in to offer him extra support and feedback on his lessons.  Melissa (his swap coach), his home coach (Nicole), and I all sat down and discussed the email and Melissa apologized for anything that made him feel uncomfortable and explained that she just wanted him to receive feedback in a way that helped him grow. He then said that he thought we all had been talking about him, since he had mentioned to me that the train stop we take (in Harlem) was dangerous sometimes, but she told him that he had also told her that during their debrief conversation. He said that wasn't true, and she repeated some details about what block he lives on and a conversation they had about a park in Harlem, which he never had with any of the other staff, myself included.  He then said he felt like the email indicated that he was being targeted and that it was decided that he would be kicked out of the program already, and I explained that wasn't the case at all. That while that email was not intended to be sent to him and we were all sorry for any discomfort it caused, the point of it is that we wanted to find the best and most effective ways to support him and his development throughout the Summer. I then reiterated that we as staff do not decide to kick people out and reexplained how the process of evaluation works.  He said he understood and we talked about additional ways that Sean and I could support him (we both did extra reviews of his lesson plans before and after that email incident, did extra informal obs, etc.).

Chad also repeatedly said that Nicole did not provide him with Feedback the first week on his lesson plans, though she shared it with him in google docs. He did not tell her for several days that he was unable to find the feedback. Once he did bring it to her attention, she began emailing him his feedback directly, rather than putting it in google docs, to accommodate his difficulties with locating the feedback.  She spent several extra hours over the course of the summer revising his lesson plans with him and giving him explicit teaching suggestions--many more hours than she was required to and certainly more than some of her other Fellows received.  Sean and I spent extra time supporting him as well.

I'm happy to give any additional information that you need--just let me know.
Thanks and talk to you soon!

Lilly

As Shakespeare said, 
"All the world's a stage,
And all the men and women merely players;
They have their exits and their entrances,

A person really shouldn't spend his whole working life squeezing profits out of financial markets. I believe this is an appropriate time for me to make a change in career path. Unfortunately, since there is no feedback in the NYC Teaching Fellows program application process, it's difficult to guess what was lacking in a previous application. Since I was "knocked out" at the phone interview stage, I assume that failed on some aspect of the questioning there. Judging from the tone of the questions, it seems one is supposed to answer that it is possible (or even to be expected) that a new teacher would have a 100% success rate in achieving academic excellence in a typical NYC classroom. In the rapid-fire pace of a phone interview, perhaps I was unable to make clear the distinction that I was trying to emphasize: while each individual student has the potential for achieving academic excellence, one should not be unaware of the statistical unlikelihood of realizing that potential in every student in a large class. While a 100% success rate with a large group of students is, of course, the aspiration of every teacher, in everyday life it is more likely a red flag for cheating than an outcome of hard work.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
There are 3 major factors that motivated me to reapply to the Teaching Fellows Program.  These major factors are:  
1) My love for kids,
2) My love for teaching, and
3) My strong belief, that thru education all things are possible and all students can perform at a high level no matter what their circumstances are if they are given the love, dedication, resource, and tools needed to succeed.
I love working with kids because their personalities are so colorful and they arent afraid of anything.  They also have a different outlook on the world than adults and I love seeing the world thru their eyes.  My love for teaching started when I began tutoring class-mates after-school.  I enjoyed helping them better understand the course work and get better grades.
When I graduated from college and became a restaurant manager I found a lot of joy in training and developing my employees who were interested in getting promoted and becoming managers.  When I worked at Starbucks Coffee company management candidates would request to train with me because they knew they would get the best training from a manager who would give them her all, who was organized, who knew how to give feedback and knew how to teach someone at their level.  
It had always been a dream of mine to open a daycare center.  This dream became a reality in 2009.  This experience further solidified my love for children, my love for teaching and my belief that thru education all things are possible and all students can perform at a high level no matter what their circumstances are if they are given the love, encouragement and tools they need to succeed.
All of my students in my daycare came from a low-income community.  I was faced with the challenges of poor student attendance, students coming to daycare hungry, parents not being able to consistently pay for daycare or pay on-time.  I also had children in my daycare with special needs.  I fought thru all of these challenges.  How?  My students who didnt attend school on a regular basis I sat with their parents every chance I had to instill in them the importance of their child coming to school on a consistent basis.  Poor attendance equals poor academics, their child falling behind.  Students who are constantly absent tend to have lower math and reading abilities.  Students who came to daycare hungry I fed them, no questions asked.  I pointed their parents in the direction of government assistance, or any other programs I could think of that could help them.  Parents who had a hard time paying for daycare I kept their kids for free because I didnt want their child to fall behind in their learning and development.  I also assisted these parents with getting child care vouchers or I negotiated a fee they could afford.  I did not want their child to be left behind.
I also had children in my daycare with various disabilities.  I worked with their parents and specialists to help ensure their growth and development.  I did all of these things because my desire for children to succeed no matter what is unwavering.  Even though I no longer operate my daycare my parents still keep in contact with me to let me know how their kids are doing and it makes me proud.  So these are the reasons why I decided to re-apply to the Teaching Fellows Program.

I think I misread the eligibility when filling out the last application because I was told I was not eligible even before I got to the end of the application. I am stronger candidate because I have spent the past year in a academic setting as a tutor corp fellow Great Oaks Charter School as well as my years of experience as a tutor during college.
I was motivated to reapply because I feel that I am more confident and prepared this time around. Since then, I have continued working with students of different age groups in a number of subjects.

RRIssueLogBody297:
Laura:

We had a bit of a weird situation yesterday.  There was a Fellow - Anand Vyas - who statistically speaking flew right above the PIP line all summer long, so he never was sort of "flagged" by our staff as a Fellow of serious concern that would have required any sort of extra formal intervention.  He struggled on his last two observations, and it hurt him enough where he may have fallen below the 2.2 threshhold, to which "additional evidence" is considered.  Moreover, the coach did not recommend him for completion of PST when she logged the last observation into TT2.

It was sort of a perfect storm...he was never really given any feedback that his completion of the program was in jeopardy, until he sort of bombed the last observation - after which the coach also decided to not recommend him for a position this fall.  I had a conversation with him on Friday (the last day, of all days), and tasked him with calculating his own overall PST score using the math from the handbook.  I also told him that if he falls between 1.9 and 2.2, he'll have to have additional evidence considered, after which an overall decision will be made.  He understood the ramifications and the next steps.

I've also tasked the coach (Shinair Francis) with formally compiling all the evidence that led her to that decision (late lesson plan emails, conversations, instances where he didn't implement feedback) so that she can share it all with me.  

In my honest opinion, Anand was not given ample notice to really make adjustments.  With a decision of this magnitude, you'd like to have a paper trail of evidence so that the Fellow in question knew all along that things were not going well, so that he/she could have attempted adjustments before it came to this.  Blame for that can fall on my shoulders, and also on the fact that he was close to the PIP line, but never under it.  What would you like me to do?  Can I be in the loop once all the evidence is gathered and considered?  it may be moot - he may have done well enough on Technique Assessments/Anchor Technique Assessments to cover up the one low observation towards the end - but I'm not sure.  

Again, let me know.

JB


Jonathan Barone
NYC Teaching Fellows
Training Academy Director

RRIssueLogBody194: Alex came in for an outplacement follow up conversation on 8/23. Alex was professional during the conversation and expressed confusion about his final score and outplacement decision. While Alex said he calculated his score he was very close to a 2.2, his score ended up as a 2.06. We talked about the different measures we take into account and how that score is determined. He asked to see the comments his Coach and TAD shared but I explained this was shared in confidence but we could send his scores to him in an email. Alex expressed that he did not understand this and hoped that meeting would shed light on what went into his decision. I shared that was what I was hoping to do but that there is some information that we are not able to share. Alex asked about what I had in front of me and I shared that I was looking at essentially a summary of all of the information that went into his decision. He shared that he would like to see that as well and I explained that I wasn't able to share that as it included some of the confidential feedback shared by his NYCTF staff. Alex left still expressing some confusion. While I made clear this was an issue of him not meeting the performance bar, I think he left hoping to learn things that we simply don't share with Fellows. I did my best to be clear about this but I got the impression Alex may have felt as though information was being withheld even with my explanations of what we shared and ensuring that his scores were sent to him over email.

On Tue, Oct 18, 2016 at 3:52 PM, Courtney Moore <courtneyleith.moore@gmail.com> wrote:
Hello Dana,

Let me begin by saying, I had no intention of resigning from the program nor did I ever want to resign from the school, but I had to what I thought was best for me, and more importantly, the students.

Just to inform, and maybe give a little understanding, the school placed me with three subjects. Three of my of my classes were ICT classes of 30 students and I did not have a special Ed teacher in the room with me. All of my three geometry classes were seniors who had already passed geometry, but had not passes the reagents. Needless to say, the students were shut down before I could even try. I could not get a handle on any of these classes as I had no maps or direction on where to begin with lessons. The dean and AP came in to one of my classes and gave them a "talking to," but to no avail, and possibly made it worse as students started throwing papers at me as soon as they left. 

Was it unprofessional to resign on a whim? Yes, but my hope is that the school would take a better look at these classes and see how affected the students learning was. All I want is to be a teacher, and a great one at that. I was so honored to be a part of the fellowship and worked so hard at setting myself up for success, but if I had stayed at that school for another day, I know all that passion would have been gone before I could develop into the teacher I know I can be.

I'm not sure if asking for a chance to find another school in January, and stay with the fellowship is even an option. If there is a way to appeal. It breaks my heart to think that I failed, but it's not a decision I took lightly. Just know I was failing the students by being there more than leaving. 

Either way, Dana, I greatly appreciate you taking the time to read this email and hope to hear from you.

Regards,

Courtney Moore

David"

The attached doctor's note from Dr. Robert Grossman stated that the physician requested that David have an appointment with him due to an urgent medical issue, and should be medically excused for 7/26. I responded to David via email on 7/28 stating that he can remain in the program but any additional tardies/absences will result in removal from the program.
RRIssueLogBody3100:
David wrote in on 7/26:

"I have had a prior absence, and then a lateness and left for a doctors appointment during the day. Those are noted in my account. I'm incredibly ill today. I can't get dismissed from the program. This is my life's calling and I already have a job. Please, I will bring a doctors note tomorrow. 
I have to apologize profusely. I have something called cluster headaches, which I was diagnosed with years ago. I started to have symptoms again last week. They manifest like a cold, and then hit like a jackhammer in the back of my eye. Last night I took medication and was managing this morning. Then like a drill was placed inside my brain I got one of the worst headaches of my life. When I take my medication, it drops me like a fly for hours. I'm going to the doctor at 2 pm today, but I'm knocked down for the day. Please give me this chance. This was beyond unpredictable and I'm truly sorry. Thank you very much for understanding."
RRIssueLogBody4103: I called David to speak to him about his 3 absences (two absences and 22 min late). He disputed the absences, saying that he was only 15 minutes late but that there was a security sign-in at the building before the sign-in in the library. He also disputed the second absence saying that he was there but was out at a doctor's appointment for an hour and a half and only missed part of his planning time.  He also felt targeted, like he was just getting caught, while other people were doing the same thing and were not getting caught. He also felt like his coach was trying to push him out of the program. I encouraged him to speak to his TAD or other staff in the building for additional support and to discuss the absences with his coach or TAD. I also reminded him of our policies and shared that moving forward he really needs to focus on attendance. He asked if he was being kicked out and I said no but he has to be present moving forward. He was upset, but not rude, throughout the call.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I did not go through the interview process before, because it came at the time when we decided to move abroad for my husband's job.

I was very impressed with the group interview process and feedback provided, and it still seems to me that becoming a fellow is something that would be highly desirable. Since my last application in March 2015, I have gone through experiences at work and have had conversations with those close to me (family and friends), which further motivated me to chase my dream of teaching mathematics. My mother was the most influential in this department. She taught in NYC for over 25 years, and since retiring to Florida in 2006, she still continues to teach computer sciences part time at a local college. My mother told me that being a teacher is what it's all about in life; you help others around you and receive the satisfaction of having those students remember you years later.

I last applied to NYCTF for the June 2011 program, and was signed up for an interview when an illness in the family brought me home to DC, prompting me to withdraw my application. As it turned out, I was able to return to New York in short order, and my career took a sudden turn to work on campaigns for LGBT rights here.

Several years later, I returned to school and received an MFA in Creative Writing from Rutgers University. I began teaching writing through the Rutgers Early Access College Humanities program this winter, and have never been more sure that I belong in the classroom. REaCH provides college level, credit-bearing courses to Newark high school students who aspire to be the first in their families to attend college. Teaching them has been a challenge and a pleasure. To put myself through school, I have also been working as an SAT tutor for a very different populationalmost exclusively wealthy families in Westchester and the city. This tutoring experience has provided valuable skills, particularly in teaching writing mechanics, but it simply cannot compare with how rewarding REaCH has been. 

As I reapply to NYCTF this year, I can say with confidence that I want to teach, that I want to teach where Im needed most, and that I can make a real difference in the lives of high-needs students. This program is the ideal path for doing so.

Q13: 

     There are always two sides to every argument. The discussion is on to ban single-sex classrooms or to allow single-sex classrooms into the public school system. Each side has strong logic on why their argument is correct. And the side that has the most compelling information, and research is on the topic of not to segregate boys and girls in the classroom. The other side has compelling argument, but not enough proof in what is being stated in order to have single-sex classrooms. I choose the side of not to segregate the boys and girls in classroom, because the facts are in place and the evidence shows real time outcome.  
     With intergraded classrooms in public schools it has been shown the best way to teach children as individuals is to focus on each learning style rather then there sex. It creates a proper learning environment, and the child will excel in the class due to the different learning styles, and diverse personalities. Single-sex class takes away from stereotypes such as boys liking to play football, and girls liking to dance. Students deserve the chance to explore other opportunities in school that they would not the chance to in a single-sex school.
   The authors in both articles have valid points on why classroom should, and should not be single-sex. Each reason is very compelling. Banning single-sex classrooms will allow students to explore the other sex, and open to new activities. Not banning it will allow for structure, and a lower divorce rate. Each side is compelling.


Q14:  

     
       Looking at history single-sex schools was the way to go.  It worked for those who were of high class, and wealthy. Now that we are in the 20th century times have changed along with idea and style of education. With this public school districts should not segregate boys and girls in the classroom. There are many reasons to this, which include sex discrimination, stereotypes between genders, and economic privilege. For the most part it can do more harm then good.
    According to The National Association for Single Sex Public Education states that the number of public schools offering single sex schools in the U.S lowered to 500, offered single-sex educational opportunities for the year of 2011-2012. This is in part due to the stereotypes that are reinforced. It is becoming popular in the low-income areas. These are issues that the public school system has to deal with on a daily basis. From a 2011 article in the Journal Science concluded that sex-segregated education is deeply misguided; sex segregation increases gender stereotyping, and legitimizes institutional sexism.
   On the other hand single sex classrooms may provide some great benefits such as schools have order with the uniforms, a ridged discipline, and a sense of togetherness. When students share a classroom or school with another gender it allows to students to branch out on their interest in activities, learn a skill they never knew they had. Boys can learn about home economics, and girls learn about mechanics. There needs to be diverse learning styles. Dont segregate the public school classrooms, there is so much more room for growth.
"

Hello Lauren, 

I apologize as I am only seeing this now. :( 

Hagai's rating improved tremendously for his last observation due to, in part, many of the most difficult students being absent that day. During that day, there were 11 students, as oppose to the regular 14-16 students. 

For Classroom culture, most students complete the task and what the worksheet he was asking them to complete. Only one student in a back corner was off task. They were following behavioral expectations and directions (except for same said student). Students were continuously working as he gave them multiple problems in varying difficulties. He did have to remind them to continue working on other problems after they finished the first one (their pick) but they did so. 

For essential content, I always consider Hagai to be strong in this aspect, nonetheless, it was difficult to assess because his CT was continuously changing topics and asking them to not do Algebra work but what would be considered 7th-8th-grade work. -- As a note, she had very low expectations of the class and eventually said she did not want to recommend anyone to take the Regents even as that's essentially why they were in that class for. The lesson was focused on quadratic equations and how to find the answers or zeros. 

The content did advance students toward grade level standards and goals as well as the activities (problems) were directly related to what he wanted them to reach. Like I mentioned earlier, I think this is Hagai's strong point and he constantly helped his other two Fellow teachers with the planning of their lessons. He also translated the work and put directions in Spanish as the majority of the class only spoke Spanish and understood limited English many of them did not verbalize concepts in English. 

For Demonstration of Learning, 

Although most students did not verbally participate, this could be their language as most of them did not speak English, they did have answers written that worked and follow the explanation/model Hagai had provided them. If students completed the task he created, as they were, Hagai would be able to have data that would give him information (data) on how well the students understood the lesson. The only part that I would consider a growth is the academic writing and explain their work. 

Hopefully, this provides some info, again, the main factors were: difficult students missing, lesson planning directly relating to Algebra 1, and his addition of multiple level problems to get data.

RRIssueLogBody194: I called Ayesha as she has been absent from PST for three days. She said she wrote to her TAD letting her know she was withdrawing. When I asked her why she said she felt overwhelmed and that she was not getting enough support from her Coach or staff at her site. She also felt like her coach was talking down to Fellows and did not appreciate being treated like the students. I asked if she had expressed these concerns to her TAD and she said that her TAD was very busy and she therefore did not want to bother her.

Erika Abelon and I spoke with Katherine today about her outplacement from the program. We let her know that there is not an appeals process, but that we were happy to answer any questions she had.

Katherine asked what additional evidence we considered, and we shared that we considered her performance as well as her professionalism concerns and her professionalism concern letter to determine a holistic picture of her readiness to enter the classroom. 

Katherine shared that she believed she was getting low ratings from her home coach, and higher ratings from her swap coach. I shared that her home coach and swap coach gave her the same ratings during her final week, and that multiple staff including her LI and her TAD sat in on her observations.

Katherine shared that when she received her PIP, her coach told her that she would be successful, and that her  coach only gave her high ratings at the end because she was receiving the support of a PIP. We discussed how we as a program issue PIPs as a support so that Fellows are able to rapidly improve, so this is an expected outcome of a PIP - that Fellows would receive additional support from staff and show improvement. .

Katherine mentioned that different concerns were shared with her principal than what were in the EPT Concern Letter, so we reiterated what was in the EPTCL for her and that this is the context we shared with the principal. 

Katherine asked us if her Coach perceived the threat because of Katherine's use of her hands when she speaks and cultural tone - we reiterated that the threat was perceived based on the language of the statement she made, and was not based on her culture.

Katherine shared with us a letter that the Coach at her hiring school had written, as well as several lesson plans and notes she had written for her students.

Katherine shared that she has spoken with her attorney, and that she will likely be filing a written complaint. She expressed concern that she had spoken with Jill Custodio and Laura Rincon earlier in the summer about her concerns with her coach, and asked how we follow up when concerns such as this one are raised.

Katherine showed us a document on which she had documented her concerns with her Coach. When we asked if she had shared that with the program, she let us know that she had not because she did not feel like she could share it with her training staff.

RRIssueLogBody3100: Katherine came into the office to talk about her outplacement. Since we had flagged that we wanted Anna or Shauna in this conversation and no one was available to handle the meeting with me, Maggie and Meha and I decided that we should tell her that we have a few people out of office and we would set up a meeting for her when someone was available. We basically ended up having the outplacement conversation anyway in the hallway. It lasted over 15 minutes and we talked through a number of the basic questions (there's no appeals process and no opportunity to reverse the decision; a team makes holistic decisions based on all the info we have about performance, attendance, professionalism, etc.; she can always go teach through another program besides NYCTF or NYCTC, etc.). She got stuck on the point that there was no option to appeal or reverse the decision because she said a friend of hers had their decision reversed. I told her I couldn't speak to other fellows, but that for the fellows in her score range, there was no appeals process.  She kept repeating this point, stating that she wanted to share all the information she had about her coach so we could get a better picture of her performance and re-evaluate her. She claimed her coach didn't like her and gave her low scores and documented things about her. She also said that she overheard her coach say things about her. She wanted us to consider the opinion of the Principal at her site, who saw the way her coach treated her. I assured her that we took into account multiple perspectives and multiple pieces of information and that the determination does not ride on one person's opinion. She also asked for her ratings and PIP and I told her we could share that with her since it's no longer available since she's been withdrawn in TT2.

Hi Dana,

Thank you for following up. Since speaking with you, I've followed up three additional times with other NYCTF representatives in an attempt to arrange accommodations.

The questions that you're asking below are ones that we already discussed in person and it doesn't appear that you've made any headway in arranging these accommodations. As I mentioned when we spoke, these accommodations take time to arrange and I'm concerned that you will not be able to adequately accommodate me. There are still videos on Blackboard that have not been captioned and that are still inaccessible to me. At this point, I'm reluctant to leave my job and invest in fingerprinting and certification exams if I'm not going to be appropriately accommodated.

To briefly answer your questions:
1) I've used FM systems since elementary school. And I've used CART services since high school.
2) I've used the FM system to reduce the signal to noise ratio and the CART system to read what I wasn't able to make out through the FM system.
3) Phonak provides the FM system. You would need to consult with them around a system that would meet our needs as I don't know what the listening environment is typically like. I've used Mirabai Knight of StenoKnight for CART services in the past.
4) I am happy to provide you with a copy of my audiological evaluation (please see attached). This is protected health information and it should not be disseminated further without my written permission.

I was never informed that I needed to reach out to the University directly for accommodations -- I will contact them today and see if I make any headway. With immersion beginning next Monday, I'm not very hopeful.

Please let me know by COB tomorrow if you've made any headway.

Thank you,
Navena Chaitoo

"To whom it may concern, 

         Good afternoon, as you may know, the New York City Teaching Fellows have unfortunately terminated me from the program as of today, August 15, 2016. I must share with you that I feel extremely disrespected and perplexed about the way I was notified about my termination from the program. If you take a look at my NYCTF and Pace University profiles this summer, they have been more than professional, regardless of all the difficulties and unfairness I was put through. For that reason, I feel that the way I am being treated by the program is not reciprocal. It is unfair and rather cruel to have received a simple termination email after being placed in a Masters degree program, teaching NYC students, and given false encouragement by my coaches and site director all throughout.  This shows a lack of transparency and frankness from the NYCTF. I also strongly believe that I was not given a fair chance since the very beginning of my placement at Charles O Dewey Middle School. My certification was General Education 7-12 Biology and I was placed in a 6th grade ELA class with 25 students, some of who had IEPs (Individualized Education Program) which are given to Special Education students. I was never notified about this, yet my coaches expected me to have 100% attention from students every time. On one occasion, my coach tried to discipline one of my most misbehaved students and she was completely unsuccessful, however this (among many things) was not taken into consideration and was graded extremely tough.  I was clearly told by my site director that the unfairness I was being put through was reported to a higher official and that the Fellows would take it well into consideration. There were also many disparities such as fellows who had a class of only 2 students, and inconsistencies about the way fellows were being graded, among other things such as clear favoritism, conjectural racism, and unfair grading. On three occasions, I heard about coaches going back to two fellow profiles to adjust their ratings. Lastly, the fact that my teacher track account has been deactivated is extremely questionable. I can no longer access ANY of my NYCTF documents and Pre Service Training performance information. I was also not told how to go about continuing my career as a teacher nor what will happen with my master's program. I have many questions. Today I am kindly asking you to provide me with an e-report that contains each and every document I submitted through teacher track as well as a full and detailed report that shows exactly how the NYCTF came about making a final decision to terminate me from the program. In the past, I have received an email back in a timely manner from the NYCTF, therefore I also expect to hear a response within three days. I am looking forward to hear from you, should I not, I will be forced to contact higher authorities, the Office of the Mayor, the NYC Department of Education, and the media. 

Thank you for your time.

Sincerely,

Tania Castillo"

Greetings Grant,

     As you may know, the New York City Teaching Fellows have unfortunately terminated me from the program as of August 15, 2016. I must share with you that I feel extremely disrespected and perplexed about the way I was notified about my termination from the program. If you take a look at my NYCTF and Pace University profiles this summer, they have been more than professional, regardless of all the difficulties and unfairness I was put through. On one occasion, my coach tried to discipline one of my most misbehaved students and she was completely unsuccessful, however this (among many things) was not taken into consideration and was graded extremely tough.

RRIssueLogBody3100:
Principal called this afternoon to discuss her concerns about Fellow's performance. She stated that the Fellow does not know how to differentiate. She observed him teach a theater class this morning - Fellow has a Theater background - and noted that Fellow does not exhibit the "basics of teaching" (e.g. lack of clear goals and objectives). Instead, he was observed spending 25 minutes trying to explain the project. The Principal asked the Fellow at the end of the observation to share his lesson plan, and he hasn't yet shared it with her as of the time of the call (~4:30pm). 

She also shared that his DOE mentor, who co-teaches a social studies class with him, reported to the Principal that having the Fellow in the classroom is like "having another kid in the class."  

I shared that his evaluation showed that he was able to engage students, and that perhaps the current school isn't the right fit, or that he could work better with middle school students, which is the age group he worked with during summer training. I advised her that if he really isn't a good fit for the school, he can be terminated but with a 10-day notice. Mid-year Fellows are not an option for her since the 7-12 SPED group are slated for D75. I shared the Hiring Support email address, as well as informed her that the New Teacher Application is launching in December so should have a small number of candidates available for hire sometime that month. She will be processing the information I provided and will share her next steps with me at a later time.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: As any teacher will tell you, it takes time to learn who your students are as people. I have been moved when I build trusting relationships with my students. I am moved when they, consciously or not, reveal their struggles to me; or when I learn their personalities and am able to recognize when they are challenged and when they feel rewarded. Despite not being accepted into Teaching Fellows last year, I am no less motivated to pursue this career path. Over the past few years of working with special and mainstream education students, I have found myself, consciously or not, acquiring and refining skills necessary for successful teaching. Communicating, relationship building, and the ability to recognize the obstacles are among these skills. While I am consistently moved when seeing my students succeed over academics and personal challenges, what drives me to pursue this career is that I am energized by being the force that helps them achieve these successes. This year, I am no less confident that I will make a successful teacher and have a positive impact on the students who find me at the head of their class. Since I last applied I have had more practice planning lessons and am more prepared to assess what is necessary for a lesson plan. I believe I will come into the interview with a solid plan and deliver an effective lesson, earning myself a fellowship and setting in motion a rewarding and successful career.

RRIssueLogBody194:
Willie emailed in on 7/19 stating:

"Hello,

In Mary Olivers poem, When Death Comes, she writes that when death comes, I want to say all my life that I was a bride married to amazement.

When asked to think about finishing the sentence last week, I teach because I could only think of Mary Olivers poem. I think about how the most thrilling and most rewarding moments in my life have come from this sort of amazement. This scary, yet so important ability to be excited by not knowing. I teach because I want my students to be comfortable not knowing. I want my students to be excited by the thought of being married to amazement.

Im writing to let you know that I wish to withdraw from the New York City Teaching Fellows.

Im not a match for NYCTF for a few small reasons: I bristle at acronyms, clapping in unison makes me grumpy, and Ive never been a good candidate for bureaucrat.

Im not a match for NYCTF for some really big reasons too. 
 
I hope to never again be in a situation where Im spoken to this way. I hope this for my colleagues as well. Ive had too many interactions with coaches who were openly condescending to me. (This isnt true of all coaches, of course. Some of the coaches Ive met have been brilliant and absolutely inspiring.) But Ive had coaches talk to me as if Im lazy, as if Im a jerk, as if I couldnt possibly understand. And Ive witnessed even worse directed at my colleagues. This is exploitative, disrespectful, and it betrays all of the very hard work weve doneand the hard work weve committed to do in the future. 

I cant spend any more time with the very vocal contingent of fellows who find only time to complain about the amount of work they have to do. By overemphasizing the workload, the amount of sacrifice required to be a fellow, how this will be the most difficult thing you will do in your life, NYCTF has installed a culture of complaining about how much work there is, rather than a culture of engagement with how important and meaningful that work could be.

And despite promises of the programs rigorousness, Ive been disappointed by my university experience. Many of my colleagues at LIU Brooklyn quite obviously arent interested in doing the work of advocating for students with disabilities. Some of them have even bargained with professors to make the readings and assignments fewer, shorter, easier. Even scoffed at some of the very accommodations and services we might provide for our students. The work has not been rigorous.

Monday morning I woke up and I was sick with knowing I couldnt do this anymore. Somewhere deep down in my gutswhere my body decides right from wrongI realized I had hit my limit. I had gone in to NYCTF too many days, knowing that it just wasnt right. 
 
But my heart is broken also. I cant continue in this program, which means Im not going to get to meet the students I was excited to teach, and learn from, in the fall. Ive met some amazing New Yorkers who are, no doubt, going to go on to do amazing things in classrooms all over this city. And Ive met coaches whose students, certainly, are the luckiest. 

Im not through with educationI look forward to finding out how else I can support learning, support young weird minds bursting with wonder. And I look forward to living up to Mary Olivers challenge: When its over, I dont want to wonder if I have made of my life something particular, and real.

Thank you for everything so far.

Sincerely,

Willie Filkowski"
Is not in San Diego and is not in NYC yet - would like to update his borough preference to Brooklyn

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I was motivated to re-apply to the New York City Teaching Fellows because I am fully committed to educating special education students in high need schools and feel I can make the greatest impact in the lives of these students being in the same classroom, with the same group of students each and every day. 

I think I am a much stronger candidate this time around, because unlike when I applied previously, I am coming with some relevant classroom experience and not from the private sector. I think my experience in the classroom has made me become more open to embracing a culture of feedback, mentoring and observation in order to raise standards and expectations from students. It is a career of lifelong learning, so that you can teach others.

"Hi, I am writing to withdraw from the fellowship. I really appreciate the opportunity, and I apologize for the late notice, but I will no longer be able to do this.
Ryan"

Jeta visited Sam's site today to follow up on the concerns he raised. Her notes are below.

I spoke with Sam about his concerns about his classroom today. He shared that it has been a very challenging classroom for the summer. When asked to explain some of his specific concerns, he shared that he had been informed by his CT that there was a student who had previously been arrested off school grounds for possession of a weapon. That same student drew a gun on a name tag for his desk. Sam went to his director with these concerns and felt that the director wasnt responsive. I asked Sam what Eric specifically said or did that made him feel this way. He said that Eric shared reasons why this wasnt a severe concern and also raised that he may be making assumptions about the student. I reassured Sam that his concerns are taken very seriously, and that the reason for my visit was to address his concerns. I also shared that the Directors role is to both address those concerns and also support his reflection as a teacher.  I also shared that the site is here to support him and help him grow and develop this summer, and he should absolutely feel comfortable sharing his experiences, reflections, and concerns with any staff member, including his Director. 

I told him that we had heard that he felt unsafe in his classroom and asked him to share more about that. He said, Well, the class has made a lot of progress. I asked him if he felt unsafe now, and he said, no. 

He also shared that there were many struggling students in his classroom, ELL students, and over-age students. He did not feel that his coach took those concerns into consideration when rating him. I shared that all Fellows have different circumstances and contexts in their classrooms, and the coachs evaluations need to look at the success of the instruction and what the students are doing rather than the particular challenges that may impact that classroom. But, I also shared that his coach is absolutely there to support him in developing ways to better support and reach all of his students. 

I concluded the conversation by restating that the staff is here to support his growth and development, and he should continue to reach out to the staff at his site to identify ways to grow, improve, and best serve his students. He thanked me for taking time to visit his classroom and hear out his concerns.
Would like to placed in Brooklyn

<MSG>Good morning, my name is Brendan Cunningham and Im reaching out on behalf of all New York City Math Immersion Teaching Fellows to bring to your attention critical concerns present in the NYCTF program. 
On August 13th, we forwarded a letter addressing our concerns to an NYCTF staff member. In our letter we detailed the way in which the NYCTF program breached our contractual agreement, burdening Math Immersion Teaching Fellows with thousands of dollars in unexpected tuition costs. Therein, we asked NYCTF to honor our original agreement by paying for tuition costs associated with Math Immersion coursework and also update the website to reflect this information for future Cohorts. On August 29th, with support from our Lehman College Fellows advisor, we forwarded our letter to NYCTF top leadership. Disappointingly, over the past 6 weeks NYCTF has ceased to take action beyond limited email correspondence, thus suggesting our concerns are not being seriously considered. 
The implications of NYCTFs decision to renege on our contractual agreements are considerable and will have damaging financial impacts on Math Immersion Teaching Fellows. Furthermore, NYCTFs inaction as it relates to updating the website to accurately reflect financial obligations related to the Math Immersion program is inexcusable. As the next Cohort enters this application period, there is an equal likelihood they will fall victim to the same misleading elements that we are currently bearing the costs of. 
We would like to see a mutually beneficial solution where our original agreement is honored and the website updated. We also aim to raise awareness with the DOE-NYCTF partnership around where improvements to transparency can be made.
Weve have drawn substantial written support from Math Immersion Fellows and continue to be astounded by the lack of response from NYCTF.

He began by mentioning that he was in SPED and was teaching 6th grade math and seemed to indicate that he was switched to 8th grade math. He said he couldn't manage student behavior because he wasn't the teacher of record. I explained how we assess Classroom Culture, Essential Content, and Demonstration of Learning, and also shared that we expect that teachers are able to manage student behavior. I was very confused by what he was explaining; it was not very logical.
He then went on to say that he did not want his record to show that he had professionalism concerns and went into all the ways in which he was professional. At first I thought there was a mix-up with the letters so I asked him to read his letter to me. It's the same letter in his TT2 account which is for performance. He got hung up on the part in quotes which said that Fellows are expected to meet performance and professionalism expectations in order to remain in the program. I explained that was the handbook language explaining what Fellows must do to remain in good standing and then asked him to carefully read the next sentence that explains that he was outplaced for performance reasons - it does not mention that he does not meet professionalism expectations. He was still really confused. I re-explained three more times in different ways but he still had a comprehension issue and did not seem to understand the letter. He asked that the letter be changed and I shared that was not an option. He indicated that he wanted it changed in case someone asked him about the program as a reference. Later on, we went into this in more detail. He explained that if future employers asked for a reference from the program, he didnt want them to think he had professionalism concerns. I explained that I thought the letter was clear and I shared that it was not possible to have the letter changed. I also advised him to make a more thoughtful decision about references and indicated that I dont think we would be the most useful reference for him. He shared that employers might ask if they see it on his resume and indicated that he didnt want to have a gap on his resume. I told him it was his choice but advised that he find an employer to be a reference who would be able to support him.  
He also said that he did not understand that he would be held to performance expectations and did not know anything about the 2.2 performance bar. I referred him to the handbook p. 25-29 and explained that this is clear up front before PST begins. He also mentioned that he was continually told he was doing a good job and received positive feedback and had no sense that he wouldn't pass. I reminded him that he received a PIP. He was upset because he had secured a job and said that he felt he was not warned that he would be held to performance expectations. Again, I explained how we communicate this clearly upfront before PST and that it was his responsibility to read through the materials we provide.  
He mentioned multiple times that he would be seeking advice and pursuing other options including legal options because he felt the program was not acting professionally and wants to make sure the right information is put out there. Again, I indicated that all of this is shared early on in the program, and all of it is in writing before PST even begins. He also asked me to spell my name and position three times throughout the conversation.
