RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
My first application for the Teaching Fellows program was submitted at a time when I was tentatively considering teaching as an alternate career path - not as a committed choice. I had just been promoted from a floor level customer service supervisory position at Cach Inc. to a role overseeing a team of approximately fifty agents serving us through a third party vendor, as well as an in-house team of nine e-commerce and IT Helpdesk agents. Additionally, I had taken on responsibility for the highest-profile or most sensitive client concerns escalated from our 235 store locations or our e-commerce business, including complaints escalated to our executive team, or received through the Better Business Bureau.
 
However, in February of 2015, Cach Inc. filed for bankruptcy, and in March commenced liquidation proceedings. Our remote customer service vendor immediately canceled our contract, leaving us with no-one to answer the hundreds of inquiries we were receiving daily. I improvised - since we were too short-staffed to receive calls directly, I suggested that we create an in-house email inbox for customer emails, and import unanswered emails from our former vendor to be answered by our team. I quickly trained 2 employees from other departments and created a series of templates for our most common inquiries.  We were able to clear a backlog of roughly 2000 emails within days, allowing us to resolve the majority of our customer's concerns before closing our doors for good. When we lost our returns processing vendor shortly after our customer service partner, we re-routed pending returns to our home offices and improvised a return process to ensure that our customers were reimbursed for their returned items, and that the inventory received could be redistributed to our stores for liquidation sales. It seemed each day we lost business-critical partners, and were required to improvise solutions, all the while working  with an incomplete order management system and a skeleton crew.

I learned in that hectic time that even with limited preparation, I am able to make a positive impact by maintaining an attitude of adaptability and receptiveness. The Teaching Fellows program requires this attitude; in a matter of months, prospective teachers are required to absorb what it takes most years to learn. My experiences have prepared me to face that challenge.

When I was young, I dreamed of being a teacher. I would record my lesson plans in a composition book, and would practice with my stuffed animals using the chalkboard my parents had set up in the garage, then as I grew older, with my cousins as my pupils. As I grew older, I began to put that dream aside. Teachers don't make enough money, I thought, for the amount of work they do, and the difficulty of it. I pursued instead a career in customer service, where I was promoted quickly and paid accordingly. However, when Cach filed for bankruptcy and closed its doors, I took it as a crossroads, a call to re-evaluate my career path. What I realized was that I needed more than money; I needed a career that would allow me to make a meaningful contribution to the world around me every day. This is what led me to dust off that old dream of becoming a teacher, because teachers are on the front lines of addressing the very root on inequity, and it is difficult to imagine a more compelling contribution to society.

They are in coursework all morning and afternoon, and then in NYCTF training sessions in the evening. They have a tight schedule and cannot miss any aspects of training. If they need to be down here for an appointment, we should be able to make an exception to miss a part of coursework, which ends around 3 or 4pm. 

If Fellows are not provided security clearance by the start of summer school, we do not let them start working in summer schools (their field experience of training). If they have not cleared within the first 2-3 days of summer school, we withdraw them from the program and provide the option of a deferral to the next years cohort, pending that they clear background checks. If they do not pass background, they cannot join next years cohort. 

So given that summer school starts on 7/7 this year, we would give them to the end of the week (7/8) to gain security clearance, so we can let them know whether to report or not to summer school the following Monday, 7/11. Does that timeline work for your team?

Nuree

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I am applying to the Teaching Fellows again because I have gained more experience as an instructor.  Although I teach English composition courses as a part time college instructor I enjoy working with traditional and non-traditional students.  When I first applied to the Teaching Fellows I was unsure of myself.  I didn't think I would be able to make a difference in a student's life.  I believed that I was too introverted to teach although I love the arts and have performed my spoken word pieces (and transformed into characters) in front of an audience.  I honed my teaching and classroom management skills for two years at Delaware County Community College in Media, Pennsylvania.  I taught composition, creative writing and remedial English classes to adult and incoming traditional freshman students. In order for me to become a better instructor I solicited help from fellow instructors and former graduate cohorts who were also instructors.  I developed my syllabus days in advance and asked for feedback.  I practiced and developed my "speaking voice" so as not to appear nervous and decided to walk around the classroom instead of remaining in one place. Part of my classroom management development was incorporating student input when constructing rules for the classroom.  I developed three non-negotiable rules and asked students to contribute to the next three rules.  I used technology in the classroom such as MS Word and a projector so that my learners (auditory, visual, analytical, etc) could "see" the sentence we were developing in composition courses.  I also used the SMART boards that were provided in each of the classrooms. In my creative writing classes we read poems for example and then listened to the author read his or her piece. I brought in literary articles about said author and taught lessons concerning analyzing passages and interpreting concepts. I asked students for feedback concerning content and became transparent, meaning in my introduction I shared my background, education, goals, strengths and weaknesses (being shy).  I explained to my students that I enjoy group work and will help them as long as it is a mutual agreement.  We worked as a group throughout the semester.  

There were days when I didn't think I was reaching my students and felt overwhelmed but I continued to challenge myself to do better one day at a time.  The end result was a humbling yet empowering experience.  My students passed the courses, recommended their friends to take my classes and wrote positive notes about my teaching style.  This helped confirm that I understood the content and could impart what I knew to students! My students, in turn, made gain.  Students were comfortable with their writing skills and noticed progression in their pieces and essays.  In other words, students who were initially writing one-paragraph responses were able to develop three to five paragraph responses.  Some students whose vocabulary were limited in the beginning of the semester slightly increased.  Students were writing essay responses from a positive perspective as opposed to thinking of assignments as tasks.  

Since then, I have worked with at-risk students, taught more composition courses in New York City at CUNY (City University of New York) colleges.  I continue to receive positive affirmations from my students.  I continue to discuss ideas with my graduate cohort and colleagues.  I decided to try again because I am a successful product of the New York City Public School system.  I had teachers and principals who instilled the notion of excellence.  They taught me to set goals and work hard to attain them.  As a product of the New York City public school system I believe it is my obligation to pay it forward by sharing what I have obtained.  I have taken what I learned as a child and empowered my students.  

I have taught various students: traditional, non-traditional, ELL learners, students with various disabilities from various socio-economic backgrounds and I share the same thoughts with all of them, "We try our best in this class.  We do not say that we cannot do something because that is why we are here.  We will learn from each other and together, we will get through this semester/year.  All I ask is that you try."  At first my students think that I am using cliche sayings but they realize that I am serious about education and their well-being and in turn, they work hard.  If given another opportunity, my goal is to bring all of my experiences attained since my last application to help middle or high school attain their academic and personal goals.

RRIssueLogBody5106: I called Jnaya to issue an EPT CL and left a message. She called me back and I began to go through the talking points, explaining the issues we've seen with the EPTs (professionalism/high expectations). She immediately interrupted and asked, "do I need a lawyer or something like that?" I explained that we were just giving her a set of next steps and she needed to follow these next steps through the completion of the program. She said that she was not going to do any extra work and indicated that she was upset that she was not receiving an email from anyone in the office that she was approved to start teaching. She said she submitted a form last week. She said, "If were going to talk about professionalism right now, then your office needs to be professional, you'll have to pay me or something because I can't accommodate that right now." She then went on to explain that she already paid for a trip and that she wasn't going to do any more work. I explained that this was not extra work, but merely meeting expectations. She said she has not received word about this until today. I reiterated a few times throughout this conversation that we needed to discuss next steps and she continued to go on about the concerns. I was able to explain her next steps (I focused on the others and left out unprofessional dress). Before I got to the job search part, she said, "We dont have a consistent co-teacher and it changed from yesterday to today." She said she has already been doing these things: "I've been doing it so far" and said she would to read the letter with an attorney present and that she will go get a friend whose a lawyer from the South to come up here. She claimed this was "Slander" and that she would be getting a lawyer.  I didn't have the chance to go through the job search part (she already has a job) and did my best to end the call as soon as possible as she continued to speak rudely, inappropriately, accusingly, and remark that she would be getting a lawyer. At some point, she also said she wanted to speak to someone higher up at the office and I explained that we would have no additional information for her and that as long as she was able to meet the expectations of the EPTs, she would be able to complete the program.

RREthnicity69: Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander
RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I traveled in Asia and the Pacific for about two years while I was based in the Philippines.  Traveling made me realize just how small I am in the grand scheme of things and that I live in a world where everything and everyone is interconnected.  This realization helped me grow exponentially as an individual and as a professional.  Ultimately, I can say with the utmost confidence that traveling is the best education I received.  

What made traveling the best education for me was not just experiencing all the beautiful and majestic things in life but it was also being exposed to the bad and ugly things in the world.  I experienced and saw the evilness in people when they are pushed to a corner in their lives.  I saw how easy people lose track of their humanity in exchange for money.  This set of experiences was not easy to take in, and it certainly made me think twice of what I was doing, but I have never felt more alive than I did when I was traveling so I kept moving forward.  It was only until after the second anniversary of traveling that I realized that the bad and the ugly were probably the best lessons I can learn from in life and I did just that, and it led to my continued growth.  

I think being exposed to the world is the best education for any of these students in low-income communities.  I remembered the epiphany I experience when I first traveled, when I realized that the world was so big and so is my potential to make an impact on people.  Many of these students, similar to myself at their age, lack ambitions and inspirations because they are expose to very little in life and therefore their imagination is also limited.  I am ready to become an educator, and a mentor.

RRIssueLogBody194:
Erica came in to meet with Anna and I on 8/25 to discuss her outplacement decision. She was disappointed to learn the decision was not able to be appealed and came in with a lot of evidence she had collected, like student test scores from the end of summer school exams, letters of support from other Fellows she worked with and anecdotes from her cooperating teacher. We explained that the decision was final and that many of those items arent considered in her final decision. Anna brought the conversation back to the review process as described in the PST Handbook and made clear that the reason Erica was outplaced was because she didnt meet the bar for performance. 

Erica was professional and calm throughout the conversation. She was assertive about the outplacement decision feeling unfair after sacrificing so much to be a part of the program. We explained that the outplacement decision in her case did not have to do with challenging her dedication or commitment to the program, but was an issue of her not meeting our performance bar, not showing growth and not effectively applying feedback from her coaches. 

She continued to express dissatisfaction with the process of review and described feeling in the dark while the process was underway. Erica asked a number of questions like, what number passed the external review, what is the evidence that allows someone to pass the review as opposed to me and asked to be sent both her performance scores and a transcript of the meeting. We explained that there was not a transcript for the meeting and that we couldnt share the performance of the overall cohort. We also again referred to the different elements we assess in the holistic review and described that decisions for Fellows under review are made carefully on an individual basis. 

Erica shared some frustration about the coaching process. She mentioned that she was placed on a PIP in the last week of PST and was not able to find time with her coach to discuss. We asked if she had followed up with her TAD about this issue and she said she had but not received a response. Erica also asked to see comments from her Coach and TAD but we explained that we collect those in confidence. Erica added that she had a number of behavioral issues in her class, a classroom of more than 30 students and rarely had enough materials available to her like calculators and text books. Erica explained that even with those circumstances she felt as though she had done everything she could and was surprised that her TAD and Coach didnt agree. 

Erica shared that learning this news came as a surprise to her hiring principal as well. She feels as though she is left to scramble for a job after giving so much to the program and missing the mark by such a small margin. She is following up to email some of the documents she brought along to the contact form. In conclusion Erica shared that she felt the Fellows program put her in a very difficult position. She felt that, at the bare minimum, I could have more information about what the review process involves. It doesnt feel holistic. We ended by sharing some other teaching pathways she could consider and thanking her for coming in to talk.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I am applying again, because I'm determined. I want to get in this profession because when I see young kids all the time on the train and at my job, I think what are they thinking? How are their parents talking to them? I have been around children my whole life since I was 7. I have a proclivity to it that I can't ignore. I was 7 years old and I had a class of teddy bears that I taught subtraction to. I never thought as an adult that I could do it, since I'm naturally shy. I am a stronger candidate now because I have so much more to give than the last time I applied. I wanted to be accepted into teaching fellows, but I was shaky and unsure. I psyched myself out. I thought maybe I can, but I didn't feel a sense of confidence. Now, I have had so much life experience that has made more of a dynamic person. I have a job at an Allergy practice in Manhattan, and it taught me life skills that I think made me realize what my strengths are. I truly like being around the public. People have said that I radiate positivity which I am so thankful for, because it took so much personal growth to come to this stage in my life. My outlook on life is so much more different. I like to say that my life didn't get much easier in terms of all my personal struggles going on at once but my skills in dealing with them has. I want to share. I love children, because I remember being one as if it was yesterday. I had mentors who didn't give up on me. It's my turn and I want it.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77: I applied to become a New York City Teaching Fellow 5 years ago. I am not only a stronger candidate than I was 5 years ago, I am a stronger person. I am less shy and more confidant than I was when I first applied. I have gained so much more experience working with high school students and I have a better understanding of the challenges that young people face. I have been working in television for almost a decade now and that makes me a strong role model for kids. I had a dream. I worked hard. I accomplished what I wanted to accomplish. Now I'm ready to pass on my love of learning and hard work ethic to the next generation. I want kids to see that you might grow up the child of a teen mom, getting public assistance, dealing with domestic problems but you can still do great things if you work hard. If I can achieve my dream of editing and producing work that is seen worldwide, why can't these kids?  They can and they will with the right support. I want to be there for them, so I am trying again.  I am nothing if not persistent.

At 31 years old, I currently have the most important role; a mother to two beautiful children. I applied to the NYC Teaching Fellows program when I had recently graduated college and obtained a Bachelors degree. At the time, I was a young mother of a boy named Michael. Michael, who is now 11 years old and a 6th grade student has taught me, that the more involved I am in his studies, homework, and projects, the more he will excel and be motivated to obtain higher grades. My daughter Mia is 6 years old and is currently in first grade. She is very independent, wise and I continue to encourage her to keep striving for the Os (outstanding) in her report cards. When I first applied to NYC Teaching Fellows, I did it because I wanted to make a difference and transform lives. I felt strongly about education and knew that if I overcame any obstacles anyone can too. However, I was faced with a new challenge when my son was diagnosed with Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder. After the diagnosis, my life turned upside down and I feared that my son would be negatively labeled and not be able to receive the same education as his fellow classmates at the time. Those were my feelings until I educated myself. My son has developed into a smart, bright, and social pre-teenager. I have learned to be patient, tolerant, and most importantly very involved in his education. I understood, that the lack of involvement in his daily activities, not giving him the tools that he needs, and not being in constant communication with him and his teachers would affect his grades significantly. Together we work on school projects, homework assignments, and other areas where he requires support. I recognize that the connection that I have established with the school has helped him perform to his fullest potential. Having this experience as a mother serves to say that it makes me a much stronger candidate to share my knowledge, support and experience as how an involved parent can make a world of a difference.

RRIfYesStrongerCandidate77:
I had applied many years ago, partly at the encouragement of my wife who was a teacher in a NYC private school.  I had helped her throughout her education and assisted her in classrooms reading and working with the children.  She felt at the time that I would be a good teacher and we both felt that the teaching career was a noble and rewarding endeavor. Having spent my career in business, NYC teaching fellows was a good way to enter education as a career so I applied.  I am not sure of why I was passed over, as no feed back was given, I had continued my career with Verizon.  

In 2006 we relocated to Florida as my wife accepted a job in Tampa and I purchased a restaurant to start the next phase of my career.  Having to manage 25 employees, most who were young and many growing up disadvantaged, taught me more about managing people than the prior 20 years that I spent in Verizon or in Bars in NYC.  I had engaged the community that we were located in and was a natural to mentor and encourage the young adults looking for a way to help themselves. Using methods my wife had taught me, including modeling, gearing the information based on prior knowledge and experiences as well as setting high standards and positive encouragement allowed me to bring a unexpected high level of service into my establishment. My staff was culturally diverse, as was the clientele, young and exceptionally well prepared to handle what was expected from them as young adults in society.  Education was always put first, their hours were dependent on maintaining good grades in school.  I am proud that I was able to encourage and prepare a great percentage of my former staff for college and life beyond.

Thank you for your prompt response. Based on this information and the sequence of events that have transpired with regards to Teaching Fellows candidate Denise Alvarez, I have some serious concerns/questions in order to best be prepared for the staffing challenges ahead. 

We currently have 8 vacancies, but weve hired many Teaching Fellows throughout this OOT hiring season. According to the advisement that Denise Alvarez has received from Department of Education officials and possibly the Teaching Fellows, I believe we may be facing a state of emergency with regards to the staffing of our school. 

Basically, this means that all other teaching fellows currently on-boarding with 10X080 have the same option to go elsewhere from now to September 6.

From P weekly
Guidance on 30-Day Advanced Notice Requirement for Pedagogue Resignations
